<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0257</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sentence Review for Convicted Terrorists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government will
review the life sentences of dozens of convicted terrorist prisoners
in this British province, officials said Sunday.
   The Life Sentence Review Board will review the records of the
Special Category inmates over the next six months and report back to
Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Tom King, his office reported.
   No reason was given for the review, but it appeared aimed at
reducing tensions.
   The Special Category laws for suspected terrorists in Northern
Ireland's sectarian warfare were introduced in 1972 after inmates
staged a hunger strike at Belfast's Maze Prison, demanding to be
treated as political prisoners.
   Their special privileges include political status and allow them
to avoid prison work, wear their own clothes, have extra visits and
food parcels and to live in isolated groups.
   In 1976, the Special Category status was ended for crimes
committed after that date and in 1980 no more prisoners were
admitted to the category.
   There are now 90 Special Category prisoners compared with 1,500
in 1975. There are 31 members of the outlawed Irish Republican Army,
27 of the mainly Protestant Ulster Defense Association and 32 from
the outlawed Ulster Volunteer Force.
   All but five are serving life sentences or are detained on orders
of the secretary of state.
   The predminantly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to unite
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite the province with
the Irish Republic, which is overwhelmingly Catholic.
</TEXT>
