<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--MysteryCircles     06-05 0181</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Mystery Circles,0185</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientist Says Crop Circles Caused By Whirlwinds, Not Flying
Saucers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mysterious circles of flattened crops in the
British countryside over the centuries have been caused by
stationary whirlwinds and not ghosts or UFOs, a scientist said
Saturday.
   About 50 of the circles, with diameters of 10 to 100 feet, show
up every summer usually in fields of long grass, barley, oats or
wheat near hills, said tornado expert Terence Meaden.
   Speaking at a conference in Oxford, he dismissed speculation the
circles were caused by flying saucers, helicopters flying upside
down, supernatural beings or even herds of rotating hedgehogs, a
small porcupine.
   ``Wind usually blows round both sides of a hill and merges
smoothly round the other side,'' Meaden said. ``However, sometimes
there is a gust on one side but not the other which creates vortices
or sudden whirlwinds. These sink to the ground and flatten crops in
a spiral.''
   Meaden said the Tornado and Storm Research Organization at
Bradford in northern England, where he works, investigated 150 crop
circles over the past eight years.
</TEXT>
