<2ND_LINE>AM-Alligator Attack,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four-year-old Dragged Into Pond By Alligator, Officials Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ENGLEWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An alligator grabbed a 4-year-old girl
walking along the shores of a pond and dragged her underwater
Saturday as two horrified playmates watched, police said.
   The girl, who was not identified, remained missing after an
extensive search, Charlotte County deputies said.
   She was walking at the edge of the pond at the Gardens of Gulf
Cove development at about 6:30 p.m. when the alligator lunged from
the water, said sheriff's Capt. Robert Miller.
   ``The child was forcibly dragged into the water by the
alligator,'' Miller said. ``Our rescue units and dive teams have
conducted an extensive search and the child has not yet been
located.''
   A neighbor, Debbie Triplett, said the girl's 6-year-old brother
and a friend who is about 7 witnessed the attack. The children were
walking a dog, she said.
   Another neighbor, Nolan Jesse, said when he heard the girl's
mother screaming he went to the lake and saw a 10- to-12-foot
alligator surface twice about 20 yards away but saw nothing in its
mouth. He said that the third time the gator came up, he saw a
light-colored object in its mouth.
   Deputies and neighbors said gator prints and the child's shoe
were found at the scene.
   Divers searched for three hours among the weeds in the freshwater
lake but failed to find the alligator, Miller said. Six Florida Game
and Freshwater Fish Commission agents and several deputies and
emergency workers also participated.
   The search was scheduled to continue Sunday, Miller said, adding
that the child is still listed as missing and is not presumed dead.
</TEXT>
