<1ST_LINE>u i AM-NewZealand-Earthquake     06-05 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New Zealand-Earthquake,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquake Sets Off Landslides, Blackouts and Shatters Windows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLINGTON, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake triggered
landslides, shattered windows and caused power blackouts in the
lower half of New Zealand's south island on Saturday, officials said.
   The quake measured 6.5 on the Richter scale, but damage was
limited because the quake was centered on the sparsely-populated
area of Lake Te Anau, north of the town of Invercargill, officials
said.
   There were no immedate reports of injuries.
   Murray Lowry of the Wellington Seismological Observatory said
Sunday that aftershocks could be expected to continue for as long as
a month.
   The Richter scale measures ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   An earthquake of 6.0 on the Richter scale can cause severe damage
and a 7.0 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of widespread
heavy damage.
</TEXT>
