<2ND_LINE>AM-Phones At Last,0243</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Illinois Bell Restores Regular Service To Remaining Hinsdale
Residents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HINSDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Telephone technicians restored service just
after midnight Sunday to the last of 35,000 western suburban
customers whose phones were disrupted by a Mother's Day fire,
company officials said.
   ``It went very smoothly, and everything should be back to normal
now,'' Illinois Bell spokeswoman Pat Montgomery said early Sunday,
shortly after the final adjustments were made at the Hinsdale
switching station.
   By throwing the switch at midnight, Bell hooked up the last set
of subscribers in Hinsdale and five other west Chicago suburbs. The
customers would be switched to new state-of-the-art digital
equipment at the Hinsdale station, which was ravaged by fire May 8.
   ``Technically, this should be the end of it,'' said Hilary
Anderson, an Illinois Bell spokeswoman. ``We are putting everybody
back in service ... but there might be some little glitches that we
will have to work out.
   The switching station equipment connects local and long distance
calls.
   Half the Hinsdale customers were connected to the new equipment
at midnight May 26, but the other half continued to suffer impaired
phone service, including sporadic dial tones and static on the line.
   The company promised rebates to customers for the disruptions,
but several businessmen upset about their losses have filed lawsuits
charging the telephone company was negligent in failing to staff the
switching station at the time of the fire.
