<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Israel-ArabAmerican 2ndLd-Writethru a0724 06-05 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Israel-Arab American, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0724,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Rules Awad Deported</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs of detail on deportation case and libel suit,
background on uprising.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's Supreme Court on Sunday upheld a
government decision to deport Arab-American Mubarak Awad, an
advocate of civil disobedience toward Israeli rule in the occupied
territories.
   The court said it will delay the deportation until next Sunday,
apparently to give Awad time to appear in court for a civil libel
suit against the Israeli daily Maariv.
   Awad, 44, responded to the ruling by saying, ``I am not
disappointed. I will continue to fight for a Palestinian state
wherever I am.''
   The decison by the three-judge panel was read in a 10-minute
session only hours before U.S. Secretary of State George P. Shultz,
who protested the deportation order, was due to arrive in Israel to
pursue a peace initiative.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir ordered Awad deported May 6, after
the Arab-American was arrested the previous day and accused of
playing a role in inciting the six-month-old Arab uprising in the
occupied territories.
   The Jerusalem-born Awad, who also has a home in Wapakoneta, Ohio,
has denied the charges.
   Awad describes himself as an adherent of the late Indian leader
Mohandas K. Ghandi's philosophy of civil disobedience. He has
authored a widely-circulated pamphlet called `Non-Violent
Resistance: A Strategy for the Occupied Territories.''
   In a statement from jail after he was ordered deported, Awad
said: ``For Prime Minister Shamir to say that I, a Christian, will
be forever prevented from returning to my city of Jerusalem to pray
in my holy places is totally unacceptable.''
   Awad was born in Jerusalem when the city was ruled by neighboring
Jordan. His appeal against the deportation was considered by his
lawyers to be a test case for the status of Palestinians under
Israeli rule in the city.
   Israel annexed east Jerusalem after capturing the sector of the
city from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East War.
   Israel's grounds for deportation was that Awad failed to renew a
tourist visa that expired last year. Awad's attorneys, Jonathan
Kuttab and Avraham Gal contended he did not need a visa and should
be allowed permanent residence because he was born in Jerusalem.
   In issuing the deportation order, Shamir's spokesman Avi Pazner
accused Awad on May 7th of helping to compile a series of leaflets
urging Palestinians to throw stones and firebombs at Israeli targets.
   According to U.N. figures, 201 Palestinians have been killed in
the uprising. Three Israelis have also died.
   Awad's American-born wife Nancy Nye responded by telling
reporters last month that her husband was committed to non-violence
but also to the ``intefadeh,'' which is Arabic for uprising.
   She said Awad supported measures such as merchant strikes and
boycotts of Israeli goods which matched Awad's philosophy of civil
disobedience.
   Awad's Israeli lawyer Avraham Gal won court approval to delay his
client's deportation, pending another hearing in a $100,000 libel
suit.
   In the suit filed last week, Awad challenged Maariv for claiming
in an article on May 13 that he dealt in drugs and channeled the
proceeds to the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</TEXT>
