<HEAD>Candidate's Half-Brother Charged in Attack On Murder Witness</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds two new grafs after 10th graf pvs, bgng A duty xxx, with
more detail on charge and arrest of alleged attacker; picks up 11th
graf pvs, Morton said, but subs last graf to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL PAGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The half-brother of Democratic presidential
candidate Jesse Jackson was arrested in Greenville, S.C., and
charged with hiring someone to attack a murder witness, police said
Sunday.
   Noah Robinson, 45, was arrested late Saturday night and charged
with being an accessory to a felony, obstruction of justice,
intimidating a witness and criminal conspiracy, according to
Greenville Police Detective Keith Morton.
   Morton said Robinson, a small businessman in Greenville who has
also worked in Chicago, is suspected of hiring someone who slashed
and stabbed a woman who was a witness to the execution-style murder
of a man who had worked for Robinson.
   ``We think he was responsible for the solicitation of the act and
took part in the arranging,'' said Morton.
   Robinson, who gave police a home address in Chicago, and Jackson
have the same father. Jackson, who has spoken frequently on the
campaign trail of his beginnings, was born out of wedlock to a woman
who had an affair with the candidate's father, who was married at
the time.
   Jackson and Robinson have had a chaotic relationship over the
years, at times working together but also quarreling and staying
apart.
   Jackson had Robinson take control of the federally funded
Breadbasket Commercial Association Inc., an arm of Jackson's civil
rights group, Operation PUSH, that helped minority firms bid for
public contracts.
   But Jackson was quoted as saying in 1987, when Robinson was
reportedly being investigated for allegedly violating federal
bankruptcy laws, ``I have no connection with him.''
   Bob Borosage, a Jackson campaign spokesman, declined to comment
early Sunday.
   A duty officer at the Greenville, S.C., Detention Center said
Robinson was being held Sunday in lieu of $100,000 bond, although
Morton said prosecutors planned to seek a higher bond.
   The warrant filed late Saturday charges that Robinson ``did
advise, counsel, urge encourage or otherwise aid a co-defendant in
the commission of a felony, assault and battery with intent to kill
... and later rendered assistance to the co-defendant in absconding
the jurisdiction.''
   A man turned charged with assault and battery with intent to kill
in the attack turned himself in to authorities in January, according
to the Greenville News.
   Morton said Robinson was arrested after statements from
``co-defendants'' and that more arrests are expected.
   According to Morton, Janice Denice Rosemond was stabbed
repeatedly in December 1987, after she had testified before a grand
jury in Chicago about the slaying of Leroy Barber.
   Barber was shot to death in January 1986 outside a plaza in
Greenville Robinson owns.
   ``From what we understand, there had been several altercations
over the years between Barber and Robinson. He had been working for
Robinson in Chicago and come back to Greenville,'' said Morton.
``They'd gotten into a fight a couple of weeks before'' Barber was
shot.
   Morton said Barber was shot once in the head by an unidentified
assailant and ``Rosemond, unfortunately, was a witness to that.'
   No one has been charged with the Barber slaying, said Morton.
</TEXT>
