<HEAD>Rescuers Find More Bodies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with two more bodies found</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BORKEN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers on Sunday found the bodies
of eight more miners killed in a powerful coal mine blast, bringing
the confirmed death toll to 45 in West Germany's worst mining
accident in 26 years.
   Six men who survived three days in an underground air pocket were
rescued Saturday after a microphone lowered into a shaft picked up
their voices and tapping sounds.
   Peter Carl Ruehland, a spokesman for Preussen Elektra, the
company that owns the mine, said rescuers were continuing the search
for six miners still missing since the blast Wednesday.
   Residents of Borken, 70 miles northeast of Frankfurt, were to
hold a service later Sunday to remember the victims of the tragedy.
   In an interview with the ZDF television network, surviving miner
Ahmet Batkan said he and the five other miners contacted rescuers by
radio just hours after the blast, but that the rescuers apparently
thought the six were with the search teams.
   Officials said the survivors were trapped about 500 feet
underground in an air pocket away from carbon monoxide estimated at
50 times the level fatal to humans.
   Officials said about 200 workers were involved in the search in
Borken, a town of 15,000 people.
   The Borken explosion is the worst West German mining accident
since 299 men died in 1962 at the Luisenthal mine in Saarland state
along the border with France.
</TEXT>
