<1ST_LINE>u i BC-Soviet-TrainBlast 1stLd-Writethru a0731 06-05 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviet-Train Blast, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0731,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>More Than 50 People Killed When Freight Car Explodes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 9 grafs of detail.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A freight car exploded as a train approached a
station east of the Soviet capital, killing more than 50 people,
injuring hundreds more and throwing cars and trucks into the air
like feathers, Izvestia reported Sunday.
   The government newspaper said the accident occurred at exactly
9:30 a.m. Saturday and the blast was so powerful it broke windows a
quarter-mile away.
   It said the cause of the explosion was as yet unknown, and gave
no hint of what the freight car that exploded might have been
carrying.
   The blast occurred as the train neared the station in Arzamas,
about 240 miles east of Moscow, Izvestia said.
   ``At its very epicenter were trucks and cars, which were waiting
for the train to pass,'' Izvestia said. ``They were scattered about
as though they were down.''
   As a result of the explosion, Izvestia said, ``more than 50
people were killed, and hundreds were wounded.''
   More than 80 doctors were airlifted by helicopter to the accident
site from the regional center of Gorky, Izvestia said.
   The explosion destroyed nearby homes and businesses, set off
small fires in many places, derailed other freight cars and damaged
the rails, Izvestia said. Driven forward by the blast, the
locomotive was flipped end over end and landed beside the tracks.
   Firefighters manning a dozen fire trucks managed to douse the
main blaze about a half-hour after the explosion, the newspaper said.
   A mobile hospital able to care for 230 people was quickly set up
near the accident scene, it said.
   A special government commission was created under the deputy
chairman of the Council of Ministers, Gennady G. Vedernikov, to
determine the causes of the explosion and deal with the
consequences. Vedernikov's high position indicated the seriousness
of the accident.
   He told Izvestia local residents instantly offered to help
victims of the explosion by donating blood and food.
   People left homeless by the explosion have been placed in
apartments, Vedernikov said.
   A special ``operations group,'' military units and the local
civil defense are directing relief work, Vedernikov said.
   The 14-member government commission includes representatives of
the Health Ministry, police, the Ministry of Defense, the
prosecutor's office and other agencies.
   ``A thorough investigation is being conducted into the causes of
the explosion,'' Vedernikov said. ``I cannot yet say anything about
the results.''
</TEXT>
