<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Shultz     06-05 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Shultz,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Arrives For Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz on Sunday
urged Israel to end its occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip
and restore rights to Palestinians.
   ``Now is the time for further progress toward peace,'' Shultz
said at Ben Gurion International Airport near Tel Aviv after he
arrived for a seven-hour visit to pursue his Middle East peace
initiative.
   ``The continued occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip and
the frustration of Palestinian rights is a dead end. To continue it
is an illusion,'' Shultz said.
   ``The United States has put forward a plan for negotiations. No
party has the luxury to turn aside a chance to negotiate.''
   Israel seized the West Bank and Gaza Strip during the 1967 Middle
East war. Since anti-occupation unrest broke out in the occupied
lands on Dec. 8, Israeli soldiers have killed more than 200
Palestinians. Two Israelis have been killed.
   Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres greeted Shultz. ``We look
upon you as a man with a message, a man who carries a message of
peace to all of us,'' he said.
   Peres said there was a choice ``between the continued arms race,
fanatacism, fundamentalism and other manifestations of extremism and
the tough decision required to block this trend and to offer the
Middle East Arabs and Jews alike a different future.''
   Before Shultz arrived, Peres, who heads the leftist Labor Party,
told Israel radio, ``I will do all I can to advance the peace
process. ... Let's say the peace process dies, then what's the
alternative?''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir, however, who objects to parts of
Shultz's plan, told Israel radio Saturday he does not expect a
breakthrough.
   Shamir, who heads the right-wing Likud bloc, objects to trading
land for peace. He also opposes a proposed international peace
conference in which Western countries would mediate a settlement of
the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   On Sunday, Shamir's spokesman Yossi Ahimeir said the premier
``greatly welcomes the visit, the efforts Mr. Shultz is making to
advance the peace process.''
   Ahimeir also said Shamir will will raise Israel's concern about
the use of chemical weapons by Arab states and their newly-purchased
medium-range missiles.
   ``He (Shamir) feels that the whole free world should raise its
voice against the use of these weapons'' by Arab states, Ahimeir
said.
   Shultz is also expected to report to Israeli leaders on Moscow
summit last week and the talks he held in Cairo, Israeli officials
said.
   Peres told Israel radio he was encouraged by changes he said he
has detected in the Kremlin's approach to the Middle East.
   The Soviet Union broke diplomatic ties with Israel during the
1967 war, but gradually has resumed contacts over the last two years.
   After the Moscow summit, Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev also
said he would consider ``regularizing'' ties with Israel once an
international conference was underway.
   ``In the past the Soviet Union has been mostly a weapons supplier
to the Middle East,'' Peres said. Now ``they (the Soviets) support
compromise. This is a real change.''
</TEXT>
