<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-US     06-05 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-US,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libya Denounces U.S. For Terrorist Allegations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya on Sunday denounced the United States for
saying that groups supported by Libya were suspected in recent
attacks against Americans and U.S. facilities around the world.
   The official JANA news agency, monitored in Rome, said the
allegations were made to undermine Libya, hinder Arab unity and
force Libya to retreat from its ``support of the massive popular
revolution in occupied Palestine.''
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said in Washington on
Friday that groups that have received support from Libya were the
``prime suspects'' in recent attacks against U.S. and western
European interests in Europe, Latin American and Africa.
   She did not accuse Libya directly but said suspicion of its
continued support of terrorism was accompanied by ``concrete
evidence.''
   Mrs. Oakley referred to the seizure last November in France of a
shipment of Libyan weapons allegedly intended for the outlawed Irish
Republican Army. She also cited reports that suspected Libyan agents
were arrested carrying bomb-making materials in Senegal in February.
   JANA said the statements affirm again the U.S. government's
``reliance on the language of threat in international dealings.''
   ``We interpret this new threat by the U.S. administration against
Libya as a start of aggression ... without any justification but
hatred and the spirit of domination and racism,'' it said.
   For years, Libya has been one of a few nations identified by the
State Department as sponsors of terrorist groups. The Reagan
administration has accused Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi of
fomenting terrorism.
   In April 1986, U.S. warplanes attacked his personal living
quarters in Tripoli. He was not hit.
   Around the second anniversary of the attack, there were several
terrorist attacks on installations and clubs owned or frequented by
Americans.
   Among the targets hit this year were U.S. Information Agency
offices in Costa Rica, Colombia and Peru and a club frequented by
American servicemen in Naples, Italy.
   Five people were killed in the Naples attack. Two Americans were
wounded in an attack on a club in Khartoum, Sudan, last month, and
the office of a U.S. bank in New Delhi was also targeted.
</TEXT>
