<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-88 1123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     06-05 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sixteen Soldiers Killed In Rebel Ambush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BACOLOD, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels ambushed a platoon
of soldiers trying to retrieve a hijacked truck Sunday, killing 16
and wounding eight in one of the bloodiest rebel attacks this year,
officials said.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
troops managed to fight back and killed an undetermined number of
rebels during the hour-long battle on an isolated mountain road.
   Foreign Minister Raul Manglapus charged that unidentified
European governments were indirectly financing communist rebels.
Manglapus made the accusation on the third day of a conference among
representatives of 13 Asian, European and Latin American countries
that have won their freedom from dictators.
   A sketchy military report said 24 soldiers and militiamen were
traveling on foot when they came under fire from an unknown number
of New People's Army guerrillas outside Silay city, 300 miles
southeast of Manila and about 25 miles from Bacalod.
   The rebels fled when more troops backed by helicopter gunships
and armored personnel carriers arrived, the report said.
   Residents of nearby villages evacuated their homes as troops
continued to hunt the rebels after the battle, which began at 2
p.m., the officials said.
   Local radio reports said the ambushed soldiers were on their way
to retrieve a truck loaded with fertilizer that rebels abandoned
after hijacking it Saturday night. The truck belonged to one of the
biggest sugar producing companies on Negros island.
   The New People's Army is one of 12 Marxist groups that have been
waging a 19-year insurgency in the Philippines.
   The National Democratic Front is the umbrella organization for
the groups. The Philippine military estimates that the front
received $15 million in aid last year from groups in Europe, the
United States, Japan, Australia and New Zealand.
   Manglapus said foreign aid to the rebels came from
non-governmental organizations but noted that such groups in Europe
are subsidized by some governments.
   ``This, of course, is practically an official flow of money, and
our armed forces and intelligence agencies tell us that this takes
place regularly in a systematic manner,'' Manglapus said.
   He said he has filed formal protests with the European
governments concerned but did not identify any of them. He said he
has not raised the matter with the U.S., Japanese, Australian and
New Zealand governments but did not say why.
   Earlier, Greece's representative in the conference denied claims
by the National Democratic Front that Greece's governing Panhellenic
Socialist Party was among its supporters.
   ``We have nothing in common with insurgents and, therefore, we
deplore such cheap and shameless lies,'' said George Lianis,
Greece's ambassador to Japan.
   Other countries attending the conference were Portugal, Uruguay,
Honduras, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, El Salvador, Nicaragua, Spain,
Argentina and the Dominican Republic.
   South Korea, the United States, Norway, Switzerland and were
represented as observers.
</TEXT>
