<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-88 1202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Meese-Candidates Bjt   06-05 0698</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Candidates, Bjt,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Senate Candidates See Meese As Liability</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Senate candidates, increasingly
concerned about political fallout from Edwin Meese's legal problems,
are beginning to call on the attorney general to leave President
Reagan's Cabinet.
   At least four GOP candidates have urged Meese to resign and
others have hinted they would like to see him go.
   Leading Republicans such as Vice President George Bush and White
House staff chief Howard H. Baker Jr. have conceded Meese's troubles
could severely damage GOP prospects this election year. But the
attorney general has insisted he has done nothing wrong and will
remain in office until he can ``set the record straight.''
   Independent Counsel James McKay is expected to issue his report
this month on Meese's conduct. Sources familiar with the probe said
the report would not recommend an indictment but would raise
questions about Meese's ethical conduct.
   In recent interviews Meese has refused to say when he might leave
office, but has ruled out a departure before his name is cleared
``because people would say there was something wrong.''
   Meese's strongest defender in the administration is Reagan, who
has said that ``only a complete change of (Meese's) character''
would prompt him to ask his old friend to resign.
   However, that view is not shared by many Republicans involved in
tough election campaigns.
   Bush said he met early last month with Meese, and the attorney
general assured him he would do nothing to jeopardize the vice
president's presidential campaign.
   In a recent interview, Bush also said that Meese has ``been made
aware by the polls and by a lot of public comment that there is the
danger that this matter, if it stays exactly the way it is, could
not only adversely affect me, but others as well.''
   During a recent television interview, Baker acknowledge Bush's
discomfort.
   ``It's a difficult situation,'' he said on the NBC show, ``Meet
the Press.'' ``It's an unfortunate situation. It's one that
obviously troubles the vice president. But in the final analysis,
the only person who can make a judgment on this is the president of
the United States, and the president has expressed his continued
confidence in the attorney general.''
   Pete Dawkins, battling to oust Democratic Sen. Frank Lautenberg
of New Jersey, told a college commencement audience recently: ``I
believe Ed Meese should step down as our nation's leading law
enforcement officer.''
   Mayor George Voinovich of Cleveland, the Republican challenger
trying to unseat Democratic Sen. Howard Metzenbaum of Ohio, recently
declared that ``for the good of the country, the president, the
Justice Department and the Republican Party, Mr. Meese should
resign.''
   ``If Mr. Meese ever had any use to the administration, it has
long since passed ... he ought to go,'' said Slade Gorton, the
former Republican senator, trying to capture the seat being vacated
by Sen. Dan Evans, R-Wash.
   A fourth GOP Senate candidate, Bill Anderson, who is running
against Democratic Sen. Jim Sasser of Tennessee, recently wrote
Meese to say, ``I urge you to step aside and resign as attorney
general to enhance the credibility of that office as well as the
credibility of the presidency.''
   Several Republican senators have stopped barely short of outright
calls for Meese to resign.
   Sen. David Karnes of Nebraska, fighting a challenge from
Democratic former Gov. Robert Kerry, recently said he did not think
Meese was a factor in his race. But then he added, ``I'm not going
to be writing any letters saying please stay.''
   Typical of one approach was that of Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I. When
asked about Meese, the senator, who is up for re-election, said he
believes it is up to the president to decide but then adds that he
thinks Reagan might be better served by someone else.
   Sen. John Heinz, R-Pa., has said he expected McKay to issue ``a
very serious and condemnatory'' report. In that case, he said, if
Meese didn't resign, the report would go to the Office of
Professional Responsibility, which the senator described as ``a very
tough office.'' Heinz said he anticipated that office ``would
recommend that Meese either resign or be fired by the president.''
</TEXT>
