<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SoloSailor     06-05 0341</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Solo Sailor,0354</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Sails Solo Nonstop Around World</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SYD1,4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 34-year-old Australian woman Sunday
became the first woman to sail solo nonstop around the world when
she navigated triumphantly into Sydney harbor after a 189-day voyage.
   More than 10,000 people greeted Kay Cottee at the harbor. She
jumped out of the 36-foot sloop Blackmore's First Lady and onto the
dock for an emotional reunion with friends and family.
   Hundreds of small boats dotted the harbor to welcome her home
from a trip she undertook to raise money for Australian children's
charities.
   Ms. Cottee, a Sydney shipbuilder, told reporters that during the
23,000-mile easterly journey, ``I experienced real fear for the
first time ever at sea.''
   She said the worst seas came two days before she rounded Cape
Horn at the southern tip of South America on Jan. 20.
   ``It was in mountainous seas breaking in huge waves _ just
indescribable,'' she said. ``I thought the boat would roll right
over and go down.''
   But she said she enjoyed the experience.
   ``Who wouldn't be happy doing something they love for six
uninterrupted months?'' she said. ``It was a personal challenge. ...
I learned that I've got more endurance and determination than I ever
thought I had.''
   After leaving Sydney harbor last Nov. 29, Ms. Cottee had no
physical contact with other boats or people. She carried all the
dried and canned food she needed for the trip.
   Her journey also was the fastest sailing trip around the globe by
a woman.
   Ms. Cottee said she had not been lonely because she was regularly
in radio contact with family members and the Australian media.
   ``With the state of modern communications equipment, I made a lot
of friends along the way,'' she said.
   Ms. Cottee said she also had time to give up smoking, read books
and listen to music.
   Among those at the harbor to meet Ms. Cottee were Nick Greiner,
premier of New South Wales, and Hazel Hawke, wife of Australian
Prime Minister Bob Hawke.
</TEXT>
