<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-88 1401EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Dukakis-Defense     06-05 1016</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Defense,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis May Find Himself Depicted As Leftist on Defense Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis could find himself
depicted as far to the left on critical questions of defense and
military strength in the fall race for the White House.
   His opposition to many weapons systems already has drawn fire
both from Republicans and within his own party.
   Dukakis, rejecting characterizations of him as naive and
reluctant in the use of American power, says he wants to enhance
U.S. conventional forces while keeping defense spending stable and
wants to rely on the cooperation of allies in cases of potential
international threats.
   The likely Democratic presidential nominee does not shrink from a
foreign policy debate with the expected Republican nominee, George
Bush. He already has begun attacking him on the administration's
Iran-Contra affair and Central America policy.
   But while nationwide surveys give Dukakis an edge over Bush, the
one area in which voters continue to place more confidence in the
Republicans than the Democrats is military strength and dealing with
the Soviets.
   ``It's clearly an issue that's there to be exploited,'' said
Norman Ornstein, a political analyst at the conservative American
Enterprise Institute. ``I think this is potentially the soft
underbelly of Dukakis.''
   Will Marshall is issues director for the Democratic Leadership
Council, a group of defense-minded Democrats led by Georgia Sen. Sam
Nunn and others. Marshall said Dukakis' attitude on foreign affairs
questions gives some Democrats concern about Dukakis' ability to
project resolve and a willingness to intervene unilaterally, if
necessary.
   ``His strong stand on Europe and conventional forces makes him
obviously not a George McGovern, not an isolationist,'' Marshall
said.
   ``But on Third World, regional conflicts, and Latin America, he
tends to strike a very legalistic, moralistic posture that raises
questions about what is the best way to protect our national
interests and support the spread of democracy.''
   Bush has portrayed Dukakis' views on defense as akin to those of
McGovern, the Democrats' 1972 peace candidate who lost in a
landslide.
   ``Even Jimmy Carter and Walter Mondale supported (weapons)
systems that Governor Dukakis opposes,'' Bush said. ``The governor's
views are naive at best, and if implemented would be dangerous to
the defense of this country.''
   Dukakis and his campaign parry the issue back at the vice
president.
   ``We feel strongly,'' said Dukakis communications director Leslie
Dach, ``that the real vulnerabilities on foreign policy are on the
Republican side. They've got to explain away (Panamanian leader
Manuel Antonio) Noriega, Iran-Contra, and a failed and unpopular
policy in Central America.''
   Jesse Jackson, Dukakis' only remaining Democratic rival, has
accused Dukakis of avoiding specifics on many issues. But it is on
defense systems where the two may be closest, with Jackson also
opposing major new weapons systems and calling for cuts in the Star
Wars nuclear defense program.
   Dukakis held a meeting on defense issues last fall with a group
of Democratic defense specialists, including veterans of past
administrations and think-tank experts.
   One participant, speaking only on condition he not be named, said
Dukakis and the experts didn't seem to connect.
   ``There was certainly a kind of ships passing in the night
feature to it, to put it mildly,'' this Democratic defense
specialist said.
   He said Dukakis' remarks generated concern about an ``idealistic
view of rule of law in foreign policy _ that although the personal
styles and attitudes and demeanor are very different, that he's
really very similar to Jimmy Carter. I think that's what people are
worried about.''
   Not everyone who attended the meeting felt that way. Some have
come to be Dukakis campaign advisers.
   ``He seemed to be open minded, to be willing to listen, but not
to be terribly familiar with the issues,'' said Robert Komer, a
former undersecretary of defense who is now a consultant at the Rand
Corp.
   Dukakis has focused on beefing up the U.S. conventional military
forces _ taking a page from the book of Nunn. Dukakis wants to
enhance air and sea support, and supplies such as ammunition, for
U.S. troops, said Madeleine Albright, Georgetown University
professor of international relations and Dukakis' senior foreign
policy adviser.
   He believes ``some targeted new investments are necessary,'' but
will not estimate their price, she said. He does not call for cuts
in overall defense spending but would keep the Pentagon budget
``stable'' for several years, financing his projects from cuts in
Star Wars and other systems, she said.
   However, speaking to senior citizens in Massachusetts in mid-May,
Dukakis suggested services for the elderly could be paid for from
military cutbacks.
   ``Are we going to spend $6 billion on Star Wars and MX missiles
on railroad cars, or are we going to build affordable housing for
families of low and moderate income and the elderly?'' he asked.
   Dukakis opposes both the MX and Midgetman missile systems and is
against plans to add two more aircraft carriers and the support
ships that go with them. Although it is too late to stop the B-1
bomber program, Dukakis would not favor buying more B-1s if elected,
said Christopher Edley Jr., issues director for the Dukakis campaign.
   ``His point is we can't buy everything in the defense candy
store,'' Edley said, ``that we have to make choices that really do
advance our essential security needs. And he would emphasize our
conventional strength.''
   Ultimately, individual weapons systems may prove less important
in shaping voters' judgments than feelings about the candidates'
resolve and strength.
   ``I think there's some real unease out there about where Dukakis
would draw the line in the dust,'' Ornstein said.
   In both the Middle East and Central America, Dukakis cites the
need for agreement among other nations to stop hostilities.
   ``There's a feeling Governor Dukakis places too great a store in
the possibility of solving all conflicts through negotiated
settlement,'' Marshall said.
   ``He needs to reassure people that although a Dukakis
administration would be very vigorous and dogged in its exploration
of diplomatic avenues for achieving our national interests, in the
final analysis he's willing to act decisively to protect our crucial
interests.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
