<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-88 1446EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PhonesAtLast     06-05 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Phones At Last,0648</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Back To Normal' As Full Phone Service Returns To Chicago Area</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HINSDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Real estate agent Nancy Jordan was burning
up the phone lines again Sunday and Becky Hector, expecting her
third child any minute, felt calmer knowing she could reach out and
touch someone in an emergency.
   Nearly a month after a May 8 fire damaged a switching station and
left 35,000 customers in six western Chicago suburbs without service
for varying lengths of time, the Great Phone Outage came to a quiet
end.
   At 12:01 a.m. Sunday, Illinois Bell officials transferred the
last 18,000 customers from the damaged, jury-rigged switch to a new,
state-of-the-art digital unit. With as many as 250 employees often
working around-the-clock, the company compressed what is normally a
50-week job into less than four weeks.
   ``It was a very good cutover, very uneventful,'' said Bell
spokesman Dick Hill.
   ``Thank goodness. Any more problems and I might have hit the
roof,'' said Mrs. Hector, whose exchange was among the last of six
to be transferred by Bell.
   ``Being without a reliable phone is like being without running
water,'' she said. ``You never realize how important it is until
it's gone.''
   Mrs. Hector said she had spent much of the month in her car,
running errands she normally would have taken care of by telephone.
   ``I couldn't reach the other mothers in my children's pre-school
classes for car pooling. I couldn't call to make doctor's
appointments for myself and then my own kids got sick,'' she said.
``I just started showing up at the (doctors') offices instead of
making appointments.
   ``And then when I was home, I was anxious because I'm so far
along (with the pregnancy). Even so,'' she added, ``I think I'm
going to miss some of those times when the phones weren't ringing
off the hook.''
   Not Ms. Jordan.
   ``The phone is my lifeline,'' she said from her downtown Hinsdale
office. ``When it went down, so did my livelihood. There's only so
much paperwork to catch up on, and that's how I justified the first
couple of days without the phone.
   ``Then I went knocking on doors, driving around and leaving
notes. But talk about inefficiencies. It was like a different
country just a few miles from here where people's phones were
working.
   ``I'd come over to show their house, and they'd tell me `You'll
have to come back later, we didn't have a chance to clean. Why
didn't you call us?' And I'd say, `No phones.' And they'd look at me
funny.''
   Since the Mother's Day fire, phone service had been sporadic at
best for Ms. Jordan and other Bell customers. About half were hooked
up to the new system on May 26.
   With the remainder hooked up Sunday, the utility said things
should be back to normal.
   ``Technically, this should be the end of it ... but there might
be some little glitches that we will have to work out,'' said Bell
spokeswoman Hilary Anderson.
   Although Illinois Bell promised rebates, several businesses were
angry enough to file lawsuits charging the utility was negligent in
failing to staff the switching station, which houses computerized
equipment to connect local and long-distance calls. Firefighters
reached the scene 82 minutes after an alarm registered at Bell's
Springfield monitoring station.
   And Illinois Attorney General Neil Hartigan filed a complaint
with the Illinois Commerce Commission seeking to have Bell pick up
the tab for financial losses.
   But Sunday, at least, Bell was savoring its accomplishments in
returning the area to full service.
   ``We still have a lot of work to do, but it won't be the kind of
feverish work we've been doing,'' said Hill. ``It was an
extraordinary effort by all the people involved.''
</TEXT>
