<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Protest 1stLd-Writethru   06-05 0828</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Protest, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0770,0855</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marchers Demand Release of Political Prisoners in Unprecedented
Protest</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to ADD background on previous protests,
Tatars, UPDATES with Armenian demonstration. Edits to trim. No
pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 80 Soviets shouted ``Freedom, freedom!'' and
carried banners through downtown Moscow on Sunday in an
unprecedented march to demand the release of political prisoners.
   About 50 police officers courteously stopped the protesters from
advancing to Red Square but allowed them to gather across from the
Moscow Soviet, the white-columned headquarters of city government.
   The afternoon march along Gorky Street, a major thoroughfare that
leads to the Kremlin, was the first in the Soviet capital in memory.
Participants credited Kremlin leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's campaign
of ``glasnost,'' or openness on selected topics.
   ``This protest shows how our political freedoms are widening.
Today we are making history,'' declared Yuri S. Skubko, a member of
the Democratic Union, a fledgling opposition group.
   Sweating in the sun, the demonstrators gathered near a statue of
Yuri Dolgoruky, the Russian prince who founded Moscow, and shouted
in unison: ``Freedom, freedom for political prisoners!''
   It was the first time that chanting protesters carrying banners
marched along a Moscow street without police making obvious moves to
disperse them.
   In recent months, Moscow police have allowed some demonstrations
to proceed, but they sometimes seized banners and detained
participants.
   In December, police manhandled a dozen young people who gathered
outside army headquarters to protest the Soviet military role in
Afghanistan.
   Sunday's protest sparked reactions ranging from anger to
bewilderment from Soviets strolling down Gorky Street, one of
Moscow's most fashionable shopping avenues.
   ``Are they making a movie?'' asked Dmitri Kuchov, 12.
   A flushed woman shouted at the marchers: ``This is slander! Don't
you see that?''
   The protesters started at 3 p.m. at the base of the monument to
19th century Russian poet Alexander Pushkin. Hundreds of Soviets
looked on.
   Different groups called for freedom for Armenian nationalist
Paruyr Ayrikyan; for leaders of Crimean Tatars who want permission
for Tatars to resettle in their Crimean homeland; and for political
prisoners in the country as a whole.
   ``We estimate that there are 300 to 400 of them,'' said Viktor
Kuzin, 35, a member of the Democratic Union's Central Coordinating
Council. ``Not all of them are imprisoned under political counts,
but some have been falsely accused and convicted of committing
common crimes.''
   A young man climbed a lamppost by the bronze statue of Pushkin to
lead the protesters in a chant calling for Ayrikyan's release.
   Demonstrators then marched down the sidewalk on Gorky Street,
past the Central Hotel and vendors selling apple juice and flowers,
on their way to Red Square and the Kremlin.
   Police on the sidewalk across from the Moscow Soviet blocked them
after they marched about 500 yards. The protesters then gathered at
the Dolgoruky monument.
   Uniformed police appeared to treat the protesters politely.
``Please stand over there with your banners,'' one lieutenant told a
protester after touching him on the shoulder.
   At 4 p.m., the protesters turned around and returned to Pushkin
Square. A group of Armenians then staged another rally outside the
headquarters of the Soviet news agency Tass.
   Ayrikyan, 39, was arrested by the KGB secret police in Yerevan,
Armenia's capital, on March 25. He is the founder of the Union for
National Self-Determination, an Armenian nationalist group.
   His wife, Yelena, 35, said that Ayrikyan, who has served 17 years
in prison, labor camp and internal exile for his political
activities, was being held in a KGB isolation cell while charges
against him were investigated.
   On March 19, Ayrikyan told a Moscow news conference that more
than 70 people had died in anti-Armenian racial riots in the
Azerbaijan city of Sumgait on Feb. 28.
   The Soviet government said 32 people were killed, and Mrs.
Ayrikyan said her husband had been accused of slandering the Soviet
state.
   The riots grew out of ethnic tensions between Armenians and
Azerbaijanis. Armenians have demanded that an Armenian-dominated
area of Azerbaijan be annexed to their republic.
   Mrs. Ayrikyan, her eyes red from crying, said there were reports
her husband had a heart attack while in jail, but she said officials
denied her any information about his health.
   Tass accused the groups of staging a ``concert'' for Western
reporters in Moscow to cover the 1,000th anniversary of the Russian
Orthodox Church and described Akrikyan as ``a dissident who has
declared against the policy of the Soviet state more than once.''
   ``The Criminal Code of the U.S.S.R. has no such notion as a
political prisoner,'' Tass said.
   It accused ``extremist-minded'' Crimean Tatars of calling for the
release of Sinaver Kadyrov and Rishat Ablayev and said they were
serving time ``for criminal offenses that have nothing to do with
human rights.''
   The Tatars, deported by dictator Josef V. Stalin as alleged
wartime collaborators with the Germans, have been petitioning for
years for the right to return to their Crimean homeland.
</TEXT>
