<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     06-05 0704</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says He Doesn't Mind If Jackson Keeps Campaigning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, driving toward the final
primaries and a Democratic delegate majority, said Sunday he had no
objections to rival Jesse Jackson's continued campaigning up to the
convention and expects Jackson to work for the ticket in the fall.
   ``It's not harmful at all,'' the Massachusetts governor said of
Jackson's reported intention to continue his campaign past the
primary season. ``He's a very strong person who's done an
extraordinary job of winning votes and winning support.
   ``I hope and believe we're going to have a good relationship. We
have in the past,'' he said. ``... I suspect he's going to be out
there campaigning hard for the Democratic ticket this fall.''
   Jackson, campaigning in California toward that big state's
primary on Tuesday that ends the delegate-selection season, has
indicated he intends to keep up a campaign schedule even after the
final primary and up to the Democratic Natioal Convention, pressing
his issues and seeking support from delegates already chosen.
   Dukakis holds a commanding lead in delegates, however, with more
than 1,800 delegates toward the 2,081 needed to nominate. His
campaign aides are confident that he will gain the remaining
delegates he needs to assure his nomination by Tuesday's primaris in
California, New Jersey, Montana and New Jersey, and hope to declare
a Dukakis majority has been secured.
   Dukakis campaigned in New Jersey a second day on Sunday before
flying to California in the afternoon for a final round of
campaigning in the state, where he will await the returns Tuesday
night. He planned a late rally at a Greek Orthodox church in Los
Angeles Sunday evening, and stops in several California cities on
Monday.
   He flew back home to Boston late Saturday to see his wife Kitty,
who is recovering from delicate surgery on her spine to repair two
herniated cervical discs. Dukakis said she is bothered by pain in
her hip, where they removed bone for grafting, and was walking with
the support of a walker.
   He was asked about Jackson's remarks at a news conference in
Paterson after addressing a Sunday morning crowd of about 300
people. Dukakis stood on rocks with the city's Passaic Falls
waterfalls crashing behind him.
   Dukakis said that while he expected Jackson's support, ``that
doesn't mean that he can't advocate for those causes and those
things he believes in.''
   ``I'll be doing the same. We'll all be doing the same. But I
don't see any deep divisions in the party at all. We're going to be
united as never before.''
   Appearing on ABC-TV on Sunday, Jackson campaign chairman Willie
Brown suggested Jackson should be offered the vice presidential
nomination.
   Dukakis press secretary Mark Gearan, asked about Brown's remarks,
noted that Jackson himself has said the nominee should have the
choice of selecting a running mate.
   ``Dukakis isn't thinking about the vice presidency until the 7th
of June,'' Gearan said. ``In terms of Rev. Jackson, he isn't ruling
anyone in or anyone out.''
   Jackson himself said of Brown's remark: ``That's his point of
view.''
   Dukakis later addressed about 500 people at an outdoor rally in
Montclair, a leafy suburb of New York City, and attended a
neighborhood festival in Jersey City.
   Dukakis called for government investment to revitalize the
nation's cities, citing redevelopment projects he said were
discontinued in Paterson under the Reagan administration, and the
example of the economic rebirth of Lowell, Mass., in his state.
   ``That did not happen by accident,'' he said. ``It happened
because we invested in that community, and we've got to do that in
cities all over this country, including Paterson.''
   In New Jersey, Dukakis noted that the state has elected Democrats
statewide, including Sen. Bill Bradley, who campaigned by his side
on Saturday, and Sen. Frank Lautenberg, who faces a tough
re-election battle and did not appear with Dukakis. Yet New Jersey
has not voted for the Democratic nominee for president since 1964.
   ``There is no reason the state that has given us Bill Bradley and
Frank Lautenberg can't get back in the Democratic column this year.
And we're going to make it happen,'' he said in Montclair.
</TEXT>
