<1ST_LINE>r a AM-YaleShanties 1stLd-Writethru a0755 06-05 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yale Shanties, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0755,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yale Alumnus Charged in Torching of Anti-Apartheid Shanties
^Eds: Subs the 2nd graf to CORRECT age and update with release on
bond, and Subs the 8th & 9th grafs, beginning ``Yale President,''
with 5 grafs to update with details on reaction, background.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA STOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Yale alumnus was charged with arson
Sunday for allegedly torching makeshift shanties on the Ivy League
campus that were built by students to protest South African
apartheid, authorities said.
   Dr. Elwood D. Bracey, 56, of West Palm Beach, Fla., who
apparently was visiting the university for alumni weekend, was
stopped by a jogger near the blazing shanties, police said. He was
released on $50,000 bond pending a Monday court appearance, police
said.
   Dr. Michael L. Charney, a Boston psychiatrist and class of 1968,
said he saw a man running away from the fire as he was jogging
across the campus Sunday morning.
   ``I yelled fire and ran after him,'' said Charney. ``He was in a
tan suit, tie and his class button, which he took off as he ran.''
   Charney said he caught up with the man in the courtyard of one of
Yale's residential colleges, where the two had a political
discussion about South Africa, apartheid and Yale's investment
policies.
   ``In my opinion he acknowledged he had done it and he did it
because he had strong feelings on this and felt alumni should have
their say,'' Charney said. ``He also said he had given Yale a lot of
money.''
   The man told him he had worked in a hospital in South Africa for
three months, Charney said.
   Yale President Benno C. Schmidt Jr., who had defended the
university's decision to allow the shantytown to remain standing
during a meeting Saturday with visiting alumni, denounced the arson
as a ``lawless act of violence.''
   ``To destroy them by an act of impulse is the antithesis of
reason and order that is the essence of a university or any
civilized community,'' he said in a statement. ``Beyond that, to set
the shanties on fire furtively in the midst of an urban campus is an
extremely dangerous thing to do.''
   All that remained standing after the fire was a wooden shrine
draped in the yellow, green and black colors of the outlawed African
National Congress and pasted with sheets of paper listing the names
of 250 people who have been killed in the struggle against apartheid.
   ``It was a cowardly thing to do,'' said Michael Morand, a 1987
Yale graduate who helped build the shanties as a member of the
Coalition Against Apartheid and now works in the university
chaplain's office.
   The shanties were erected in front of the Yale administration
building in April 1986 to protest apartheid and Yale investment
policies in South Africa. Officials ordered the shanties dismantled
but allowed them to be rebuilt after students agreed to maintain
them.
   Yale owns stock only in companies doing business in South Africa
that subscribe to the Sullivan Principles, a set of ethical
guidelines aimed at improving the lives of South African blacks and
ultimately at dismantling apartheid, South Africa's policy of racial
separation.
   Walter Littell, a university spokesman, was unsure how much of
Yale's stock portfolio was invested in companies doing business in
South Africa. As of 1986, Yale had about $385 million invested in
such companies.
</TEXT>
