<1ST_LINE>r i AM-LostOpera     06-05 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lost Opera,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missing Act Of Donizetti Opera Found in Cellar</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The missing second act of an opera by Italian
composer Gaetano Donizetti has been found in the cellar of the Royal
Opera House, four years after an American musicologist discovered
its first and third acts there, the Sunday Times reported.
   The lost portion of the three-act ``Elisabeth'' was discovered
last week by Australian conductor Richard Bonynge. He is currently
leading his wife, Dame Joan Sutherland, in a production of
Donizetti's ``Anna Bolena'' at the Royal Opera House at Covent
Garden.
   The Times quoted him as saying he made the discovery ``absolutely
by chance, in an old stack of ballet rubbish (music).''
   Donizetti, who was born in 1797 and died in 1848, composed the
work in 1838. The opera, set in Russia, tells the story of a young
woman's walk from Siberia to Moscow to try to win her father's
freedom from exile.
   ``Elisabeth'' first surfaced four years ago when Will
Crutchfield, an American musicologist, found the first and third
acts. It isn't known how the score of the music got to Covent Garden.
   The fact that the pages are singed indicates it may have been
near a fire, possibly one that broke out at the opera house in 1856
or one 11 years later at Her Majesty's Theater, to which Donizetti
had unsuccessfully offered the work.
   ``We are now looking for the first possible opportunity to bring
this opera before the ublic _ it will probably be within 18 months
and initially in a concert version,'' said Paul Findlay, the
director of Covent Garden.
</TEXT>
