<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     06-05 0530</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATTLE CREEK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With lots of milk and corn flakes,
Battle Creek retained its title as the breakfast capital of the
country by serving 32,697 people and beating the record set by
Springfield, Mass.
   It was the third straight year that the city beat the
Massachusetts town for the bragging rights.
   ``We placed 35,076 servings of cereal on the mall, and 2,379 were
returned for a total of 32,697 which leaves Battle Creek the
Breakfast Capital of the World,'' Breakfast Table Chairman Rick
Royal said Saturday.
   Battle Creek, home of Kellogg Co., and Springfield have swapped
claims to putting out the largest breakfast since 1977.
   On May 14, Springfield regained the title by feeding 31,279
people a pancake breakfast during its annual celebration of the
founding of the city.
   ``Congratulations to Battle Creek for topping us again,'' William
Sullivan, chairman of the Springfield event, said Saturday. ``I was
hoping for rain but we didn't get it. We feel we can outdo those
numbers and that will be our aim next year.
   ``We are not giving up,'' he said. ``We can do those numbers even
if pancakes are more difficult than pouring milk.''
   During the breakfast battles, the rules have changed. It started
out as a challenge to put out the longest table. But the Guinness
Book of World Records said a city in Spain once sat 6,400 people at
a table 7,908 feet long _ just shy of a mile and a half.
   That was more than Battle Creek or Springfield officials could
stomach, so they changed the name of their contest from the
``World's Longest Breakfast Table'' to the ``World's Largest
Breakfast Event.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. CLOUD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This little piggy going to market wanted
to be the one that stayed home, and its break for freedom at a city
intersection caused a police chase aided by broom and lasso.
   The 250-pound pig, part of a load of hogs being taken to Granite
City Livestock Sales, jumped off the back of its owner's truck at a
busy street corner and trotted off to a residential area.
   ``He must have climbed on the backs of the other pigs in the
truck, then he leaped out,'' said Dan Herrmann, a witness who helped
capture the animal after its Thursday morning getaway.
   ``It's remarkable for a pig to walk away from a jump like that
without broken legs. He must have jumped about four feet,'' Herrmann
said.
   The pig ended up in the back yard of Herb Proell.
   ``He came down the alley and then wandered up to my fence. The
cop was right behind him,'' said Proell, who was watering his lawn.
   ``I figured I could guide him with a broom and keep him against
the fence,'' Proell said. ``I was talking to him, trying to keep him
in this corner.''
   After police officers failed to grab the hog, Herrmann managed to
lasso it and put it in his truck. He took it to the livestock market
and returned it to owner Robert Steffenhagen of Foley, who had
driven off unaware of his hog's exit.
   The athletic animal was sold at auction.
</TEXT>
