<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SriLanka     06-05 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sri Lanka,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Tamils Found Slain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tamil rebels slit the throats of four
Tamil civilians early Sunday and pinned notes to their bodies
claiming they were traitors, the military said.
   Officials of the Joint Operations Command, who could not be
further identified under briefing rules, said authorities found the
four victims near a bus stop in the northern port city of
Velvettituari.
   Notes written in the Tamil language and pinned to their
blood-stained shirts read: ``This is the fate that befalls
traitors.'' It indicated that the victims were believed to be
informants for Indian peacekeeping troops in Sri Lanka.
   Velvettituari, 15 miles northeast of Jaffna, is the hometown of
Velupillai Prabhakaran, leader of the Liberation Tigers of Tamil
Eelam. The Tigers are the largest of the groups battling the Indian
soldiers, who are in Sri Lanka to enforce an accord aimed at ending
the Tamils' separatist war.
   The Indian-mediated accord, signed in July, calls for the Tamils
to lay down their weapons in exchange for some autonomy.
   Tamils, who comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people,
claim discrimination by majority Sinhalese. India became involved in
the dispute because of the sympathies of its own 60 million Tamils.
   In New Delhi, an official of another Sri Lankan rebel group
demanded the Indian government assure the safety of the Tamils.
   M.K. Eelaventhan, general secretary of the Tamil Eelam Liberation
Front, told the United News of India that there would be no one to
protect the Tamils once the guerrillas were disarmed.
   Eelaventhan said he did not want the Indian army to remain
permanently in Sri Lanka, but he expected it to help ``save us from
genocide.'' He said it would be unjustified to withdraw the
peacekeeping force immediately after the rebels were disarmed.
</TEXT>
