<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Church     06-05 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Church,0461</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archbishop Urges Solution To Panamanian Crisis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Panama's Roman Catholic
Church on Sunday criticized political restrictions and U.S. economic
sanctions, saying the crisis ``weighs heavily on the smallest
people.''
   Speaking at the traditional Corpus Christi Mass held this year in
an open field and attended by nearly 40,000 people, Archbishop
Marcos Gregorio McGrath urged Panamanian political leaders to
resolve the dispute. He said their actions ``will determine the
future of this country for generations to come.''
   The Reagan administration imposed economic sanctions against
Panama after Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, commander of the Defense
Forces, was indicted in February by federal grand juries in Florifa
that accused him of drug trafficking.
   Noriega, who controls the civilian government, has rejected U.S.
efforts to make him resign and leave the country. Panama uses the
U.S. dollar as its currency and the sanctions have brought economic
stagnation and increasing unemployment.
   People attending the Mass stood under a multicolored cover of
thousands of umbrellas for the service by McGrath and other members
of the Panamanian conference of bishops.
   The archbishop pleaded for an end to what he called ``political
restrictions inside and economic restrictions from abroad.''
   He also said negotiations to solve the crisis ``must be in Panama
and among Panamanians with the respect among the parties that is
required by any dialogue.''
   U.S. officials have been in and out of Panama meeting with
Noriega and other leaders trying arrange the general's resignation.
   Mcgrath said it was the responsibility of the Panamanian
governemnt and the opposition to seek a solution.
   ``We beg them before God and their conscience to make all efforts
to find the road to reconciliation and justice and peace for all,''
he said.
   In another development, U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Morton
Abramowitz met privately with some opposition leaders. Opposition
officials have criticized the Reagan administration, saying it
bypassed them in its negotiations with Noriega.
   One of the Panamanians at the talks, speaking with the condition
he not be identified, called the meeting a ``a U.S.gesture''
following the breakdown of negotiations between U.S. envoys and
Noriega.
   ``What can the U.S. offer now?'' he asked. ``This is just a
formality.''
   Washington purportedly has offered to drop the indictments
against Noriega if he would step down as head of the 15,000-member
Defense Forces.
   School officials said they did not expect any serious problems
Monday when nearly 700,000 elementary and high school students begin
the new school year that should have started in March but was
postponed because of the crisis.
   The national university suspended the semester and will resume
classes July 20.
</TEXT>
