<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Zimbabwe-Prostitutes     06-05 0125</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zimbabwe-Prostitutes,0128</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Legislators Propose Registering Prostitutes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Zimbabwe legislators asked the
government to officially register prostitutes to ensure they receive
regular medical checkups, it was reported Sunday.
   The parliamentarians, members of the 100-seat assembly, made the
request during a meeting to discuss health care services, according
to the state-owned Sunday Mail newspaper.
   Registration and regular medical examinations for prostitutes
would curb the spread of sexually-transmitted diseases and acquired
immune deficiency syndrome, the newspaper quoted the
parliamentarians as saying.
   AIDS, for which there is no cure, attacks the body's immune
system and prevents it from fighting infection. The majority of
those affected worldwide are drug addicts and homosexuals, but in
Africa, the disease is spread mostly though heterosexual contacts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
