<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     06-05 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Courts Environmentalists; Departs From Administration Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, with his eye on
California's environmental vote, took another step Sunday away from
Reagan administration policies by advocating a delay in a
controversial offshore oil drilling project.
   ``Before going forward with new lease sales, we must be assured
that the national treasure of the California coastline will not be
harmed,'' Bush said at a ceremony dedicating the nation's first
methanol pump at a commercial gasoline station.
   ``I have concluded,'' said Bush ``that the government ought to
defer Lease Sale 91 off the coast of Northern California.''
   Lease Sale 91 is bitterly opposed by environmentalists.
   The Department of the Interior has been pushing ahead with plans
to permit drilling off the California coast and Secretary Donald P.
Hodel planned to issue his report on sale 91 this summer, and it
could go forward by the end of the year.
   Bush advocated a delay two days before the California primary but
with more of an eye on the presidential election in November when
the state's 47 electoral votes are considered crucial to both the
Republican vice president and Democratic Michael Dukakis.
   Bush is a sure bet to sweep California's 175 Republican delegates
in the winner-take-all GOP primary on Tuesday.
   Dukakis is heavily favored to take a lion's share of the 314
Democratic delegates in his contest with Jesse Jackson.
   The Massachusetts governor has advocated an absolute moratorium
on offshore drilling.
   On the flight to California, Craig Fuller, Bush's chief of staff,
told reporters, ``George Bush recognizes the importance of
environmental and quality of life issues in California.''
   Fuller said Bush was advocating the delay ``until next year
giving his secretary of the interior an opportunity to study the
matter and determine whether or not to go further.''
   However, he said, Bush opposes ``an absolute moratorium'' like
the one called for by Dukakis.
   Bush spoke at the dedication of the methanol pump at an ARCO
station at Wilshire and Hobart boulevards.
   ``A strong domestic energy industry is essential to our national
security, and I am one who believes we've got strengthen the overall
energy base of this country and protect the environment at the same
time,'' he said.
   He acknowledged that ``sometimes these goals seem incompatible as
with the current concern about offshore drilling.
   ``I was one of the pioneers in the equipment end of offshore
drilling in the Gulf of Mexico and I know it can be done safely. But
there are other considerations _ tourism, marine life, aesthetics _
and in some extraordinarily sensitive areas, those considerations
may prevail.''
</TEXT>
