<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-88 1727EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson     06-05 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Vows To Launch Voter Registration Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson said Sunday that he will fight
at the Democratic convention this summer for a party commitment to
change practices that impede voting rights.
   Jackson, campaigning in advance of Tuesday's primary here, also
said he intends to push hard at the convention on a range of issues
he considers important, including shifting defense spending to
health care and housing, changes in party rules on delegate
selection, and campaign finance reform.
   Although he used the word ``fight'' in his speech, he modified
that in talking to reporters later, saying his quest ``for fairness
must not be seen as a fight.''
   ``Fights come when you fail to negotiate ... when people have
made a decision to go in opposite directions,'' he said.
   While putting the party on notice that he will demand a say on
several issues at the Atlanta convention, Jackson also pledged
Democratic solidarity, announcing his Rainbow Coalition would
sponsor a massive voter registration drive beginning Aug. 1.
   The drive will focus on women, minorities, young people and
laborers, he told a church congregation here.
   ``But we will go further than that,'' he said. ``In Atlanta the
Democratic party must make a commitment to empowerment _ in the
platform, in the party on the ticket.''
   He did not specify whether his reference to the ticket meant he
should be given a major say in who the Democratic vice presidential
candidate will be.
   Jackson's comments came as top campaign officials indicated a
growing sentiment that he should be offered the vice presidential
nomination if Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis becomes the
nominee, as expected.
   Campaign chairman Willie Brown, the California assembly speaker,
and state co-chairwoman, Assemblywoman Maxine Waters, both voiced
that opinion on Sunday, going beyond Jackson's own statements.
   Jackson has said he has earned consideration as a running mate,
and that he likewise would consider Dukakis if he himself should win.
   ``A lot of us around him feel he should be'' offered the vice
presidential spot, said Waters.
   Of Dukakis' contention that Jackson be weighed as a potential
running mate but will get no special consideration, she said: ``We
all know games when we see them.''
   Brown, interviewed on ABC-TV's ``This Week With David Brinkley,''
said considering Jackson should mean actually offering him the No. 2
spot on the ticket.
   ``I think consideration means literally extending the opportunity
to go on the ticket, and then it will be up to Mr. Jackson to
determine whether or not he wishes to accept it,'' Brown said.
   Asked about Brown's comment, Jackson said: ``That's his point of
view.''
   Told that Waters had said she would stay away from the polls in
November if Jackson is not treated fairly by the party, Jackson
said, ``I hope everybody will be at the polls in record numbers.''
   Jackson also said his voter registration plans will go ahead
regardless of whether he gets his way at the convention.
   In a day of appearances around the Los Angeles area, Jackson
repeatedly invoked the memory of the late civil rights leader Martin
Luther King Jr., and former Sen. Robert Kennedy, assassinated 20
years ago Sunday on the night of his presidential primary victory in
California.
   Jackson said party rules must ``reflect the example of Dr. King,
the inspiration of Robert Kennedy.''
   Jackson also said ``it is shameful 20 years after the death of
Martin Luther King and Robert Kennedy _ that we continue to deprive
many citizens of the right to vote.''
   He said he will fight for party rules changes in current
practices of dual priamries, winner-take-all threshholds, unelected
super delegates ``and other party impediments to one person, one
vote.''
   He cited studies that have found registration and voting is
effectively shut off for people in some parts of the country due to
short or inconvenient registration hours, inconvenient and far-away
locations of registration offices, and registration cutoff deadlines
a month or more before the election, before many people start
focusing on the campaign.
   Such practices are controlled at the local and state level.
Jackson urged passage of legislation in Congress that would allow
registration on election day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
