<HEAD>Two Killed In Palestinian Clashes In Beirut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrillas loyal to PLO chairman Yasser
Arafat fought Syrian-backed Palestinian dissidents with mortars and
grenades in a Beirut refugee camp Sunday. Police said two people
were killed and nine wounded.
   They said the fighting between Arafat's Fatah faction, the
largest group in the Palestine Liberation organization, and Col.
Saeed Mousa's Fatah-Uprising began shortly after midnight Saturday
in the Bourj Barajneh camp in Moslem west Beirut.
   Exploding shells shook Beirut through the night as both sides
pounded each other's positions in the camp's alleyways with 82mm and
60mm mortars and rocket-propelled grenades.
   It was not known what touched off the latest fighting. The two
factions have repeatedly clashed in Bourj Barajneh and the nearby
Chatilla refugee camp for control of the shantytowns since May 1.
   The fighting dwindled into sporadic sniping before dawn after
representatives of both factions intervened.
   Police said the two fighters killed in Bourj Barajneh were from
Fatah-Uprising. Most of the wounded were civilians, they added.
