<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's campaign chairman said Sunday the No. 2 spot on
the Democratic ticket should be his to turn down if front-runner
Michael Dukakis ends up with the party's presidential nomination.
   But Jackson, when asked about the remarks by campaign chairman
Willie Brown, said: ``That's his point of view.''
   Later, campaigning in California, Jackson told an audience at a
church, ``In Atlanta, the Democratic Party must make a commitment to
empowerment _ in the platform, in the party, on the ticket.''
   He did not elaborate on his reference to the ticket.
   Dukakis press secretary Mark Gearan, asked about Brown's remarks,
noted that Jackson himself has said the nominee should have the
choice of selecting a running mate.
   ``Dukakis isn't thinking about the vice presidency until the 7th
of June,'' Gearan said. ``In terms of Rev. Jackson, he isn't ruling
anyone in or anyone out.''
   Brown, the California House speaker, said on ABC-TV's ``This Week
with David Brinkley'' that Jackson has earned the right to be
considered as a running mate for Dukakis _ and that, he said, means
the offer must actually be extended.
   ``I think consideration means literally extending the opportunity
to go on the ticket, and then it will be up to Mr. Jackson to
determine whether or not he wishes to accept it,'' Brown said.
   Meanwhile, Dukakis was conciliatory in his reaction to reports
that Jackson would continue campaigning after the round of primaries
in California, New Jersey, Montana and New Mexico on Tuesday, when
the Massachusetts governor hopes to pick up the delegates he needs
to clinch the Democratic presidential nomination.
   ``He's a very strong person who's done an extraordinary job of
winning votes and winning support,'' Dukakis said in Paterson, N.J.,
before heading for California later Sunday.
   ``I hope and believe we're going to have a good relationship. We
have in the past,'' Dukakis said. ``I suspect he's going to be out
there campaigning hard for the Democratic ticket this fall.''
   Dukakis was within 270 delegates of locking up the presidential
nomination, while Jackson did not yet have half of the 2,081
delegates needed to win. In all, 466 Democratic delegates are at
stake in Tuesday's four primaries.
   Vice President George Bush, who has had the Republican nomination
locked up since April 26, was heading for California on Sunday as
Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III, a close political ally, again
denied that he was preparing to take over management of the campaign.
   ``No, I'm not poised to go over there. For now I think that my
job is at the Treasury Department,'' Baker said on CBS-TV's ``Face
the Nation.'' ``I can only tell you that there is no agreement, no
arrangement, no deal.''
   Bush, campaigning in Los Angeles on Sunday, courted
environmentalists with a call for a delay in a controversial
offshore oil drilling project that the administration has been
proceeding with.
   The Department of the Interior has been pushing ahead with plans
to permit drilling off the California coast. Secretary Donald P.
Hodel planned to issue his report on a lease sale off Northern
California this summer, and it could go forward by the end of the
year.
   ``Before going forward with new lease sales, we must be assured
that the national treasure of the California coastline will not be
harmed,'' the vice president said.
   He also attended the opening of the nation's first methanol pump
at a commercial gasoline station.
   Bush has had the Republican nomination locked up since April 26
and has been running alone since television evangelist Pat Robertson
suspended his candidacy on May 16.
   Nevertheless, there are pockets of lingering bitterness within
the party.
   Robertson supporters stormed the podium at the Snohomish County,
Wash., GOP convention on Saturday, where there were shoving matches
and microphone cords ripped out of the wall.
   The meeting, controlled by Robertson forces, erupted over a rule
allowing individuals to cast multiple votes for a single candidate
for state convention delegate.
