<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DesertAliens     06-05 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Desert Aliens,0489</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Found In Desert To Be Returned To Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A journey north to look for work by 36
Mexican nationals became a struggle for survival when they
encountered weekend temperatures estimated at 110 degrees in a
remote Arizona desert.
   ``I didn't know about the desert,'' said Carlos Enrique, 30,
after he and 35 others were found wandering without water northwest
of here.
   ``There is water in Oaxaca,'' he said, referring to his native
state in southern Mexico, near Guatemala.
   Most of the group, which included one woman, were in generally
good condition when found Saturday afternoon, despite having been
without food and water for nearly a day.
   Three were given intravenous fluids for dehydration at Northwest
Hospital in Tucson, a nursing supervisor said.
   ``We're glad nobody died. With this soaring heat, we responded
with everything we had in an attempt to save lives,'' said Ronald
Dowdy, chief patrol agent for the U.S. Border Patrol's Tucson sector.
   The high temperature in Tucson Saturday was 108 degrees, one
degree higher than the previous record high set in 1946.
   Officials estimated it was at least 2 degrees hotter on the
desert floor in the area in which the group was found.
   About 70 bodies have been found in the same general area since
1980, according to figures released last summer by the Border Patrol.
   The group crossed the U.S.-Mexico border apparently by jumping
the international fence about 60 miles southwest of Tucson. A
massive search was launched by U.S. officials after two men left the
main group and stumbled onto a remote ranch Saturday afternoon.
   Several members of the group said they had given up their ideas
of finding work in this country and concentrated on staying alive
after they ran out of food and water.
   Just before they were found, the group came upon a small,
stagnant pool of water.
   ``We thought, `At last, life has returned.' Even though it was
pretty ugly (the water), we drank it. The thing was to cool our
parched throats,'' said Perez Gutierrez.
   The only woman in the group, Dominga Hernandez, 18, was wearing a
printed T-shirt with a Washington, D.C., logo, but would not say
where she got the shirt.
   ``I'm looking for work,'' she said.
   Roberto Lopez, 40, said he left his wife and six children in
search of work in the United States.
   ``There is work there, (in Mexico) but the pay is real cheap,''
he said. He said he was not aware that it is illegal in the United
States for employers to hire illegal aliens.
   Lopez said his work as a laborer earned him 10,000 pesos daily,
roughly $4.34.
   Jorge Reyes Vasquez, 36, said the large group actually formed
over the course of days as several smaller groups converged by
accident in the Arizona desert.
</TEXT>
