<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-05 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sizzling Heat In The North, Chilly In The South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Low temperature records toppled Sunday across the southeastern
quarter of the nation, but far to the north thermometers rose to
record highs in Montana and North Dakota.
   Showers and thunderstorms extended from the central Gulf Coast
states across Florida, and over mountainous sections of New Mexico,
Colorado and southeastern Wyoming.
   Showers were widely scattered over northern New England and
Oregon.
   Temperatures fell to chilly record levels from Missouri to the
East Coast, including a brisk 34 degrees at Elkins, W.Va., in the
heart of the Appalachians. At some cities it was the second day of
record chill in a row.
   Other low temperature records were 40 at Asheville, N.C.; 40 at
Beckley, W.Va.; 42 at Calico Rock, Ark.; 47 at Cape Hatteras, N.C.;
53 at Charleston, S.C.; 42 at Charleston, W.Va.; 46 at Columbia,
S.C.; 46 at Fayetteville, Ark.; 52 at Fort Smith, Ark.; 48 at Greer,
S.C.; 54 at Huntsville, Ala.; 42 at Lynchburg, Va.; 47 at Mena,
Ark.; 44 at Parkersburg, W.Va.; and 51 at Wilmington, N.C.
   In the West, Sacramento, Calif., tied a record of 47 degrees that
has been on the books since 1887.
   But while people in the South may have looked for sweaters or
jackets, the northern Plains sizzled with its third straight day of
record highs, including 97 at Billings, Mont.; 98 at Williston,
N.D.; 100 at Glasgow, Mont.; and 101 at Miles City, Mont.
   And on the shore of Lake Superior, Marquette, Mich., hit a record
high of 88.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees at Klamath Falls, Ore., to 101 at Miles City, Mont. The low
for the day was 31 at Truckee, Calif.
   For Monday, showers and thunderstorms were forecast from the
central Gulf Coast region through Florida. Scattered showers were
forecast from the northern and central Pacific Coast into the
northern Rockies.
   Highs in the upper 50s and 60s were predicted along the Pacific
Coast, west of the central Rockies, and across parts of Maine; in
the 90s from southwestern Texas and New Mexico to the northern
Plains and Minnesota; in the 90s to near 105 over southeastern
California and southern Arizona; and in the 70s or 80s over most of
the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
