<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CancerSurvivors     06-05 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cancer Survivors,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Patients Celebrate National Cancer Survivors Day</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Athletes and entertainers who haven't let cancer stop them helped
people celebrate National Cancer Survivors Day around the nation
Sunday.
   ``I've tried to let people know there is life after cancer,''
said Olympic gold medalist Jeff Blatnick. ``I've dedicated myself to
showing what a person can do, and helping other people believe they
can do the same.''
   The observance was organized by the American Cancer Society and
``Coping,'' a national magazine for cancer patients.
   Blatnick, who won his gold medal for wrestling at the 1984
Olympics, joined about 150 cancer survivors and 400 patients at the
Regional Cancer Center in Erie, Pa.
   Blatnick overcame two bouts with Hodgkins Disease in 1982 and
1985. With radiation therapy, Blatnick recovered from his first
battle with cancer while training for the Los Angeles games. His
second bout was fought with chemotherapy and he is now in remission.
   Doctors said his fine physical condition helped in his fight
against the disease, according to A.J. Drexler, spokeswoman for
Hamot Health System Inc. and the St. Vincent Foundation, two
hospitals in Erie.
   Skier Diana Golden, an Olympic gold medalist and amputee, was the
star attraction at a observance at Norfolk, Mass.
   ``So many people equate the word `cancer' with death,'' said Miss
Golden, 25, who lives in Lincoln when she isn't on the road as a
full-time amateur skier. ``What we (survivors) are saying is, that's
not necessarily so.''
   Miss Golden, who prefers crutches to a prosthesis, lost her right
leg above the knee to bone cancer when she was 12.
   She won a gold medal in the giant slalom in the disabled division
demonstration event at the Winter Olympics in Calgary this year.
   Comedian Steve Allen, also a former cancer patient, agreed to
address an observance at the Rush Cancer Center in Chicago.
   ``There are over 100,000 cancer survivors in the Chicago area,''
said Dr. Jules Harris, the Rush center's director.
   Allen was diagnosed as having colon cancer in 1985, said his
spokeswoman, Christine Cody.
   ``He is in the same fortunate category as President Reagan in
that they had the same kind of surgery for the same kind of cancer,
with, happily, the same results,'' she said. ``Neither man seems to
have suffered any subsequent ill effects.''
   More than 600 people, more than half of them cancer survivors,
turned out at a five-hour picnic at Florham Park, N.J., said Lois M.
Gannon, chairman of the New Jersey division of the cancer society.
Three bands volunteered their time, the Great Adventure Amusement
Park donated clowns, cartoon characters and a robot for children,
and the Army donated a tent.
   ``It was wonderful,'' Ms. Gannon said. ``I have never talked to
so many upbeat people in my life.''
</TEXT>
