<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Violence     06-05 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Violence,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Kill 10; Troops Kill Four Pakistanis and Suspected Sikh
Terrorist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Separatist rebels killed seven soldiers
in Nagaland and another dissident group was blamed for setting a
land mine that killed three people in West Bengal, officials said
Sunday.
   In Punjab state, security personnel fatally shot four Pakistanis
and a suspected Sikh terrorist in a series of clashes, according to
reports Sunday.
   In the Punjab city of Amritsar, 260 miles northeast of New Delhi,
Sohan Singh took over Sunday as head priest of the Golden Temple,
the Sikhs' holiest shrine.
   Singh indicated he would not align himself with Sikh militants
who took over the temple complex last month and battled with police,
leaving at least 48 people dead before police gained control.
   Militant Sikhs have been waging a violent campaign since 1982 for
a separate Sikh state in Punjab. Sikhs comprise just 2 percent of
India's 800 million population but are a slight majority in Punjab.
   Suspected members of the outlawed Nationalist Council of Nagaland
late Saturday ambushed a convoy of the Assam Rifles, an
anti-guerrilla force, near Faluni in Tuensang district. Nagaland is
a remote northeastern state.
   A junior officer and six other soldiers were killed, United News
of India reported. It had no details of the battle.
   In the Darjeeling area of West Bengal, about 185 miles north of
Calcutta, a land mine believed planted by the Gorkha National
Liberation Front blew up a vehicle on the outskirts of town, killing
three civilians and seriously wounding two, UNI said.
   Gorkha militants also hurled bombs at police posts in two nearby
towns Saturday and exploded four bombs in a third town, but no one
was hurt in any of the incidents, the news agency said.
   Police on Sunday fired on five Pakistanis trying to illegally
cross the border into India in the Dera Baba Nank area, about 250
miles northeast of New Delhi, and killed three of them, news reports
said. They said the other two fled back into Pakistan.
   Saturday night, police fatally shot a Pakistani trying to cross
into India near Ferozepore, some 170 miles northeast of the capital,
the reports said.
   The United News of India also reported police killed Jagmel
Singh, a member of the outlawed Khalistan Commando Force, early
Sunday in Ludihana district, 190 miles northeast of New Delhi.
   Jagmel and a companion on a motorscooter fired on security
personnel at a road checkpoint and the officers fired back, killing
Jagmel, police said. His companion escaped.
</TEXT>
