<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Waldheim-Arabs     06-05 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waldheim-Arabs,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waldheim Receives Saudi Arabia's Highest Decoration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Kurt Waldheim of Austria,
shunned by many nations because of allegations about his actions as
a German army officer, met with King Fahd Sunday after receiving
Saudi Arabia's highest decoration.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
two leaders discussed efforts to end the Iran-Iraq war and the
Arab-Israeli conflict and also bilateral relations.
   Fahd gave Waldheim, a former secretary-general of the United
Nations, a red carpet welcome when the Austrian leader arrived for a
three-day state visit on Saturday. Fahd later hosted a banquet at
which he decorated Waldheim with the Cordon of King Abdel-Aziz, the
nation's highest decoration.
   Saudi Arabia is the fourth nation that Waldheim has visited since
being elected president in June 1986. He has been to the Vatican,
Jordan and Pakistan and has an invitation to visit Iran.
   But he has been shunned by many countries, including the United
States, which barred him from entering the country because of
allegations about his actions as a German army lieutenant in the
Balkans from 1942 to 1945.
   A historians' commission in Austria that investigated the
allegations said in February that Waldheim was ``in close
proximity'' to some Nazi atrocities in the Balkans, knew they were
going on and made no attempt to prevent them.
   But it did not support allegations that Waldheim was involved in
committing atrocities.
   Waldheim has denied any wrongdoing. Saudi Arabia and some other
Arab countries have claimed that a campaign accusing Waldheim of
complicity in World War II atrocities is being directed by Zionists
because of the Austrian president's stand toward Arabs.
   Waldheim canceled visits to Kuwait and the United Arab Emirates
after leaders of those countries were called to an emergency Arab
summit on Tuesday.
   Representatives of all Arab nations except Egypt will meet in
Algeria to express their support for the Arab uprising in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip. The uprising, which began
in December, is the only item formally on the agenda of the
three-day summit that opens in Algiers under the chairmanship of
Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid.
   The official Iraqi News Agency reported Sunday night that
President Saddam Hussein of Iraq will remain in Baghdad to direct
the war against Iran. The agency, monitored in Cyprus, said Hussein
appointed Taha Yassin Ramadan, first deputy prime minister, to head
the Iraqi delegation to the summit.
   Waldheim is seeking to bolster political and economic cooperation
with Saudi Arabia and the oil-rich Persian Gulf in general. Saudi
Arabia ranks as Austria's third non-European trade partner after the
United States and Japan.
   Waldheim has urged an early end to the Arab-Israeli conflict and
the 7{-year-old Iran-Iraq war on the basis of United Nations
resolutions.
</TEXT>
