   Progress made on arms treaties during the Moscow summit ``shows
that we've come to the special session not empty-handed,'' he said.
   Soviet leaders ``attach great importance'' to the special U.N.
session, said the foreign minister who spoke through an interpreter.
   At least 25 presidents and prime ministers are scheduled to
attend the General Assembly during the special session, but no
breakthroughs are expected.
