<HEAD>Salvadoran Bishop Says Duarte's Absence Could Encourage Peace
Dialogue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The auxiliary archbishop of San
Salvador called on his followers Sunday to pray for President Jose
Napoleon Duarte, but said the president's absence may help end the
8-year-old civil war.
   Duarte went last week to Washington for treatment of cancer.
   ``The absence of the president permits political antagonists to
not think so much about demolishing their enemy,'' Roman Catholic
Monsignor Gregorio Rosa Chavez told reporters after Mass at the
Metropolitan Cathedral.
   ``The political debate will have less passion, and that is
favorable,'' he said.
   Duarte, 62, has been in the Walter Reed Army Medical Center since
Tuesday night. He has cancer of the stomach and liver.
   It is widely presumed in El Salvador that Duarte, who is in the
final year of a 5-year term, will not be able to resume the
presidency. Vice-President Rodolfo Castillo Claramount is the acting
chief executive.
   Before discovering his illness, Duarte began talks with the two
parties beside his centrist Christian Democrats that are represented
in the legislature.
   Castillo said last week he planned to continue and broaden that
initiative with the right-wing Nationalist Republican Alliance and
the conservative National Conciliation Party in an effort to draft a
consensus to be presented to leftist rebels.
   In three fruitless rounds of talks since 1984, the rebels have
demanded a role in a broadly based transition government. Duarte has
rejected the demand, insisting that the rebels must lay down their
weapons and compete in elections.
   In his homily, Rosa Chavez referred to an all-night prayer vigil
on behalf of Duarte at the cathedral. The facade of the building was
draped with banners reading ``Duarte Lives, Today and Forever,'' and
``Duarte: God and the people are with you.''
   But only about 150 people were taking part in the visil as of
midnight.
