<2ND_LINE>AM-Teamsters-Hollywood,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Justice Department Probes Hollywood Friend of Teamsters
Boss</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An influential Hollywood figure who reportedly
stands ready to step in and resolve movie and television industry
labor disputes is the subject of a federal racketeering probe, a
newspaper reported Sunday.
   Martin Bacow, 66, has been under investigation for about 18
months by the Justice Department's Organized Crime Task Force, the
Los Angeles Times reported.
   The department has used telephone wiretaps, among other means, to
determine if he and his associates have been coercing production
companies into hiring them to guarantee labor peace, the newspaper
said.
   Bacow said the allegations are groundless and that his success at
ending costly labor problems is a natural talent. He also said he
has never been paid for his help, except for serving as a paid
consultant on the film ``Rhinestone.''
   ``If people come to me, and they believe me, and they trust me,
is there something wrong with that?'' Bacow said. ``If they want to
convict me for my God-given talents, they better bring God into
court.''
   Strike force attorney Richard Stavin, who is reportedly directing
the inquiry, refused to discuss the case or confirm that Bacow is
being investigated.
   Bacow has played a quiet role in solving labor impasses in many
productions, including such TV shows as ``Miami Vice'' and ``Magnum
P.I.,'' and on the films ``Rhinestone'' and ``Foul Play,'' the Times
said.
   Bacow says he was told by the Teamsters union that the FBI
listened in on telephone conversations between him and union chief
Jackie Presser.
   The Times also said it learned the Justice Department's organized
crime unit tapped calls between Bacow and a Los Angeles police
detective who allegedly tipped him about the federal probe.
   That detective, John J. St. John, 53, recently took early
retirement after his alleged information leak became public. Fellow
Detective Louis W. Graham, 45, received a month-long suspension for
failing to report St. John's activities, the report said.
   The racketeering probe is investigating alleged Teamsters union
involvment in film industry labor dealings and resulted in grand
jury subpeonas being served on Sylvester Stallone's film studio,
White Eagle Productions, the Times said.
   Stallone, who was introduced to Presser by Bacow and went on to
work in the union's 1986 anti-drug campaign, was not served with any
personal subpoenas.
   Subpoenas have also gone out to some entertainment industry labor
unions, including the Screen Extras Guild and the Teamsters' primary
bargaining unit in Hollywood, Local 399, according to the report.
   Bacow described himself as a retired scriptwriter and producer,
and claimed to have no affiliation with the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters, a contention supported by union officials.
   Presser couldn't be reached for comment because he is
recuperating from surgery for brain cancer.
</TEXT>
