<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Walheim-TVInquiry     06-05 0390</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Walheim-TV Inquiry,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TV-Sponsored Inquiry Says Evidence Against Waldheim Insufficient</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Waldheim-Arabs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A panel of former judges on a commission of inquiry
arranged by two television companies said Sunday there was
insufficient evidence to determine if Kurt Waldheim committed war
crimes as a German army officer.
   The panel issued its decision on the Austrian president and
former U.N. general-secretary after hearing nine days of testimony
in London in April.
   Witnesses included officers who served with Waldheim in the
German army in World War II and survivors of concentration camps and
civilian massacres.
   The inquiry was paid for by America's Home Box Office and
Britain's Thames Television, both of which screened a 3{-hour
program program Sunday night that included some of the testimony and
the decision by the jurists.
   ``We conclude unanimously that the evidence which has been put
before us is not enough to make it probable that Lt. Waldheim
committed any of the war crimes alleged against him in this
inquiry,'' the panel said.
   The five judges also found ``lapses and aberrations of memory
such as Dr. Waldheim seems to have had about his services in Greece
and the Balkans are not in themselves evidence of guilt.'' But the
commission said Waldheim ``must have known'' about German plans to
shoot captured Italian officers.
   The former judges who participated in the inquiry came from the
United States, Britain, Canada, West Germany and Sweden.
   Waldheim has been shunned by many countries, including the United
States, which has barred him from entering the country, because of
allegations about his actions as an army lieutenant in the Balkans
from 1942 to 1945.
   A historians' commission appointed by the Austrian government
that investigated the allegations said in February that Waldheim was
``in close proximity'' to some Nazi atrocities in the Balkans, knew
they were going on and made no attempt to prevent them.
   But it did not support allegations that Waldheim was involved in
committing atrocities. Waldheim has denied any wrongdoing.
   The panel that participated in the television inquiry was headed
by a retired British Appeal Court judge, Sir Frederick Lawton. Other
members were Shirley Hufstedler, a former circuit judge for the U.S.
Court of Appeals, and West German Walter Hubner, Swede Gustav Petren
and Canadian Gordon Cooper _ all retired appeals court judges.
</TEXT>
