<HEAD>Foreign Secretary Gives Cautious Backing To Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Secretary Sir Geoffrey Howe gave cautious
backing Sunday to Vice President George Bush's campaign for the
presidency.
   Interviewer David Frost asked Howe on TV-AM if Britain would
prefer Republican Bush to his probable Democratic opponent
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis.
   ``One has to be very cautious about expressing opinions on
elections in other countries because it is part of the democratic
process. One works with the leader who emerges at the end of the
day,'' the foreign secretary replied.
   ``But at this stage it would be less than human if we did not
recognize the value of working with George Bush, with whom we have
worked for a long time,'' Howe said.
   ``If there is anything in the over-simplified left-right divide
in politics, he is on the right in politics and so are we in this
country.''
   The relationship between the United States and Britain has
flourished during the 1980s under their two conservative leaders,
President Reagan and Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
