<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Ortega     06-05 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Ortega,0371</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega Holds U.S. Responsible If Peace Talks Fail</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wity AM-Nicaragua-Peace, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega said Sunday the
United States would be to blame if peace talks with Nicaraguan
rebels scheduled to begin on Tuesday fail to produce a permanent
cease-fire.
   ``We hold the United States government responsible for what
happens in these meetings'' with the Contras, Ortega said after
meeting with agricultural, industrial, health and education workers.
   Leaders of the Nicaraguan Resistance, the Contra umbrella
organization, are scheduled to hold talks with government officials
June 7-9 in Managua. It would be the fourth session held in the
Nicaraguan capital to negotiate terms of a permament truce to the
6{-year-old civil war.
   Ortega also said the Reagan administration would be at fault ``if
in this meeting the Contras do not agree to lay down their arms.''
   The rebels, trained, funded and supplied by the United States,
began their war to overthrow the leftist Sandinista government in
1981.
   Ortega said in an interview after his speech that his government
would offer ``no variations'' to its peace proposal submitted during
the last round of negotiations held May 26-28.
   The Contras turned down a government proposal for a 30-day
cease-fire extension and a plan for delivering humanitarian aid to
rebel units athered in truce zones.
   Both sides have agreed to hold their fire at least until the end
of this week's talks.
   The government agreed to discuss some of the Contras' demands for
political changes they say would bring about democratization in
Nicaragua. Those include freedom of the press, the lifting of all
political restrictions, separation of the ruling Sandinista National
Liberation Front from the army and the government, constitutional
changes and electoral and judicial reforms.
   Ortega said on Sunday the rebel delegation would be permitted to
visit leaders of the internal opposition and the Roman Catholic
Church during its stay in the capital.
   The Contra delegation planned to travel to San Jose, Costa Rica
on Monday to prepare for the talks, said a rebel spokesman in a
telephone interview from Miami on Sunday. He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
</TEXT>
