<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz 4thLd-Writethru a0827 06-05 0738</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0827,0753</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Reports No Progress In Talks With Shamir</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to CORRECT typos. Pickup 13th graf pvs ``A
Shamir...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz failed on
Sunday to persuade Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir to accept
terms set by King Hussein of Jordan for holding Mideast peace talks.
   ``I think on the whole we had a good discussion about this,''
Shultz said before flying back to Egypt from Israel. ``As far as any
major shift in anybody's position, I cannot report that.''
   Shultz said at Israel's Ben Gurion airport, ``We are going to
stay engaged and do everything we can for the balance of this
(Reagan) administration to accomplish as much as we can and leave
for our successors as constructive and positive situation as we
possibly can.''
   Shultz had two meetings with Shamir in Jerusalem in an effort to
persuade him to agree to negotiate with Jordan with a commitment for
Israel to exchange land in the occupied territories for Arab
recognition. Shultz also met in Israel with Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres, Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin and members of the
Parliament's Foreign Affairs and Defense committees.
   He told Israel in a public statement that ``the continued
occupation of the West Bank and Gaza and the frustation of
Palestinian rights is a dead-end street.'' He added: ``The belief
that this can continue is an illusion.''
   He also spoke of the prospect of another war in a region where
long-range missiles and chemical weapons have proliferated.
   The next war, Shultz said, ``will be unlike any conflict we have
seen before, involving more casualties and proving harder to
contain.''
   King Hussein, in talks Saturday with Shultz in Amman, insisted on
an Israeli commitment to withdraw as a precondition for accepting
the U.S proposal for peace talks. Shultz said he had emphasized to
Shamir ``the need for King Hussein's side to feel there is something
to negotiate about.''
   Jordan lost the West Bank, which it controlled from 1948 until
1967, in the six-day war with Israel.
   Shultz said despite his failure to persuade Shamir, ``I can
report what seems to me a very genuine desire to be engaged and to
be involved, not just for the sake of being able to say that, in a
genuine search for peace.''
   Shultz, who is based in Egypt during his Middle East shuttle
effort, will go to Syria Monday for talks with President Hafez Assad
about the faltering U.S. peace plan and the Arab summit meeting that
opens Tuesday in Algeria. Shultz hopes to persuade the Syrian leader
to take a moderate position. The secretary of state will then go to
Luxor to visit ancient Egyptian sites.
   A Shamir adviser said the prime minister and Shultz discussed
peace options but he did not elaborate. He said Shultz ``ensured
Shamir that the relations between Israel and the United States will
be strengthened in the future.''
   The adviser, Yossi Ben Aharon, accused King Hussein of attempting
to negotiate the disposition of the West Bank through the United
States. ``We prefer him to say this to us directly,'' the Israeli
official said.
   The occupied lands were virtually shut down Sunday for the third
day of a strike called by leaders of the Arab uprising to protest
Shultz's visit. It was Shultz's fourth trip to the region this year
to promote the peace plan.
   Two Israelis and more than 200 Palestinians have died since
December as a result of violence in the West Bank and in the Gaza
Strip, which Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 war.
   Shultz also called on Arabs to accept Israel's existence. ``The
belief that this can be avoided or that violence can end Israeli
occupation is an illusion,'' Shultz said.
   Peres, who backs the U.S. plan, said Shultz's mission ``sends a
loud and clear message to all listeners, a message of a hope and
choice.''
   The plan calls for an international peace conference in which the
United States, the Soviet Union, China, Britain and France, as the
five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council, would serve as
hosts. The negotiations would be aimed at self-rule for 1.5 million
Palestinian Arabs in the West Bank and Gaza, but not a separate
state.
   In a second stage, Israel and the Arabs would try to find an
overall settlement to their conflict.
</TEXT>
