<1ST_LINE>u i AM-France-Election 4thLd-Writethru a0831 06-05 0645</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Election, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0831,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Socialists Projected To Win Majority In Legislative Elections</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with new figures. Pickup 4th graf
pvs ``State-run Antenne...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Socialists and conservatives virtually split the
popular vote in Sunday's first round of elections for the National
Assembly. French television projected President Francois
Mitterrand's Socialists will win the most seats.
   Based on 97 percent of the ballots counted, the Socialists had
37.4 percent of the vote when the counting was stopped late Sunday.
The conservative Rally for the Republic and center-right Union for
French Democracy, which backed the same candidates, garnered 37.7
percent.
   The Communists took 11.2 percent and the rightist National Front
9.7 percent, with the rest going to minor parties.
   Counting was to resume Monday.
   State-run Antenne 2 network's projections gave the Socialists
between 310 and 330 seats in the 577-seat assembly. It said the
Rally for the Republic and Union for French Democracy would win
230-250 seats and the Communists 10-20, with the National Front shut
out.
   In predicting the makeup of the new assembly _ the lower and more
powerful house of Parliament _ the television network projected the
final outcome for all districts including areas that will have
runoff elections next Sunday.
   Candidates needed at least 50 percent of the vote in the first
round to win a seat in the legislature. In districts where there was
no winner in the first round, candidates had to receive at least
12.5 percent of the first-round votes to be eligible for the June 12
runoff.
   There is inevitable pressure on those coming in lower than second
to drop out and support one of the two frontrunners in the runoff.
   This system was expected to hurt the smaller parties but help the
Socialists. In 1986, before the new system was adopted, seats were
assigned on the basis of the percentage of votes won by lists of
candidates.
   Projections showed 65.5 percent of the 38 million people eligible
to vote cast ballots _ one of the lowest turnouts in recent years.
That compares with 78.5 percent in the March 1986 legislative
election and 81.4 percent in the first round of the presidential
election April 24.
   Polls had predicted a wider Socialist advantage.
   ``It's an encouraging result, but we have to consolidate it,''
said former conservative Finance Minister Edouard Balladur.
``Victory is possible if we unite. We have a week to convince all
those who do not want to give a majority to the Socialist Party.''
   Polls also predicted the Communist Party and the extreme-right
National Front _ which each won 35 seats in the last election _
would fare badly because of the winner-take-all voting system
reinstituted two years ago.
   The election came less than a month after Mitterrand defeated
former Premier Jacques Chirac, a conservative, with a solid 54
percent of the vote.
   Conservatives controlled the National Assembly from 1986 until
Mitterrand dissolved it after his re-election.
   Mitterrand had said during his presidential campaign he wanted to
work with the existing National Assembly and open the Cabinet to
non-Socialists from the political center.
   New Premier Michel Rocard formed a government with no notable
presence from other parties, however, and Mitterrand called the
election.
   The Sunday newspaper Journal du Dimanche noted in a front-page
editorial that despite the importance of the election for the
future, ``the campaign gave rise only to boredom or indifference.''
   Few issues were debated. The Socialists declared they were ready
to institute a guaranteed minimum wage, to be paid for in part with
a special tax on large fortunes. Such a tax was abolished by the
right in 1986.
   Socialists continued with Mittterrand's ``opening'' theme through
the campaign, but most politicians of the right and center-right
viewed the idea as little more than an invitation for them to become
Socialist.
</TEXT>
