<DOCNO> AP880605-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-88 1304EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DeficitMan     06-05 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deficit Man,0655</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consummate Washington Insider Heads New Commission</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The health of the economy is at risk. The
federal debt is swelling, and the politicians are gridlocked.
   What's a nation to do?
   Call in the bureaucrat!
   That may sound a little odd, but a consummate Washington insider
was required to direct the new bipartisan National Economic
Commission in its mission to cut the deficit.
   The commission director not only needed a thorough knowledge of
the budget, but had to be trusted by both sides of the political
spectrum. And, perhaps most important, someone was needed with skill
in handling giant egos.
   Enter Dave Mathiasen of the president's Office of Management and
Budget.
   Described by a colleague as ``the quintessential staff person,''
Mathiasen first worked at OMB in 1961, before it was OMB, when it
was just the Bureau of the Budget.
   He's made a career of public service, mostly at OMB but also
overseas as an economist for the Agency for International
Development. At OMB, he has worked for Democrats and Republicans,
Bert Lance and David Stockman.
   Now Mathiasen has to use that experience to stay in the
background but still guide the commission members to a conclusion on
the deficit by their self-imposed deadline of December 21st.
   The common wisdom in Washington is that the commission would
provide political ``cover'' for a tax increase and some spending
cuts, leading George Bush already to pre-emptively say he won't
support it.
   But Mathiasen says predicting the commission's actions would be a
mistake, and he won't try to read the minds of members who include
Chrysler Chairman Lee Iacocca and former Secretary of Defense Caspar
Weinberger.
   ``If you haven't decided what time you're going home tonight, I
can't forecast it. And if I do, I'm a fool,'' he said in an
interview last week.
   With the commission just starting up, Mathiasen's major effort is
to educate the members, most of whom have little exposure to the
federal budget. His staff is creating a computer game, where members
can try out different policies and instantly receive a computation
of their effect on the deficit.
   The co-chairmen of the commission are Robert Strauss, a
Washington lawyer and Democratic party power broker, and Drew Lewis,
President Reagan's former Secretary of Transportation who now heads
the Union Pacific Railroad. It will be their job to plead and cajole
the panel toward a consensus, with Mathiasen smoothing whatever path
they choose.
   The deficit commission is frequently compared in Washington to
the so-called Greenspan commission, led by now-Federal Reserve Board
chairman Alan Greenspan, whose recommendations led to the 1983
financial revamping of the Social Security program.
   The National Economic Commission has even moved into the
townhouse across from the White House where the Greenspan group was
based.
   However, Mathiasen says this mission is different.
   Social Security was facing a crisis, and there was the threat
that the checks would not go out unless action was taken. While most
economists agree that the federal deficit, $150 billion last year,
is bad for the economy, its effects are more difficult to single out.
   ``If we were able to say that on the 13th of March, 1989, the
stock market will drop (unless action is taken), then we've got a
deal,'' Mathiasen said.
   Mathiasen agrees that perhaps the most important factor in
whether the commission succeeds will be the attitude of the next
president-elect. Before taking office, the next president can
appoint two more commission members.
   The hope of the panel is to prevent its work from getting snarled
in presidential politics, but then quickly make its recommendations
to help build a consensus on how to reduce the deficit for the next
president and next Congress to enact.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880605-0082 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-88 1307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f AM-BullinChinaShop     06-05 0138</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bull in China Shop,0143</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Store Owner Plans to Let Bull Loose in China Shop</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also on general news wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PALMERTSON NORTH, New Zealand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shop owner Grant Burnett
plans to let a bull loose in his china shop this month _ literally.
   Spurred by constant bull-in-a-china-shop jokes cracked by
customers, Burnett said he will release a giant Hereford bull in his
shop on June 16 as a stunt.
   If the bull goes berserk, Burnett risks losing up to $60,000
worth of china.
   Burnett said the bull would not be drugged. It will be led into
the store by its owner, local farmer Bill Bly.
   An insurance company has agreed to cover the cost of broken china
for an undisclosed premium, Burnett said.
   ``This is something I've wanted to do for years,'' Burnett told
reporters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
