<FILEID>AP-NR-06-05-88 1354EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Harvard-WallStreet     06-05 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harvard-Wall Street,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Business School Seeks To De-emphasize Wall Street Careers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Harvard Business School is making it clear that
it wants a smaller proportion of its graduates to head for Wall
Street investment banking.
   The business school reported last week that 15 percent of its
current crop of graduates had been hired by major securities firms,
compared to about 30 percent in 1987.
   ``We don't want investment banking to be the be-all and end-all
of a Harvard MBA,'' said Margaret Lang, the business school's
director of placement.
   School officials said they began shifting the emphasis away from
investment banking even before last October's stock market crash.
   ``There was a real concern that we were being typecast as a
school for investment bankers and consultants,'' said Professor
Robert Hayes, a technology management expert. ``Our mission is to
train general managers. We were afraid of losing our heritage.''
   The changes at Harvard included improving its manufacturing
faculty, changing its admissions policies to de-emphasize financial
skills and choosing fewer people from Wall Street apprenticeship
programs.
   A decade ago, just 8 percent of Harvard Business School graduates
went into investment banking while consulting was the job of choice,
attracting 22 percent.
   But the bull market that began in 1982 and the
merger-and-acquisition binge that started soon afterward shifted the
balance.
   In 1978, Harvard students could expect to earn roughly the same
starting salary on Wall Street as in manufacturing. By 1987, Wall
Street salaries were about 10 percent higher than those in
manufacturing, but with bonuses figured in, the gap was closer to 50
percent.
   There were complaints that American manufacturing was being
shortchanged.
   ``We now have a group coming out of business schools, going to
Wall Street and contributing nothing to the efficiency of American
industry, nothing to its productivity,'' retired Harvard economist
John Kenneth Galbraith said in 1987.
   Last March, Harvard hired Steven Wheelwright, a specialist in
manufacturing, from Stanford University.
   But officials said the changes may still not funnel more bright
young graduates into the production sector.
   ``We can do all the pushing and cajoling we want,'' said
Harvard's Robert Hayes, ``but if companies do not offer jobs at
competitive salaries, the students will not go that way.''
   ``I tell students that tomorrow's chief executive officers will
be the ones who solve our production problems,'' said Lester Thurow,
dean of the Sloan School of Management at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology.
   But Thurow said his message is not taking root yet and that the
business school students still consider manufacturing a second-class
profession.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
