<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Saudi-Trade     06-05 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Saudi-Trade,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudis Report Big Trade Surplus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia posted a $2.4 billion
trade surplus last year, more than seven times the 1986 surplus, the
Finance Ministry said in a report Sunday.
   The 1986 surplus totaled $360,000, said excerpts of the report
that were circulated by the official Saudi Press Agency.
   The big increase followed a major effort by the Saudis to
diversify their economy away from dependence on oil revenues. They
have developed agriculture, wheat and food products for export, as
well as domestic consumption.
   The ministry report said exports totalled $22.56 billion last
year and imports $20 billion.
   In 1986 exports totaled $19.24 billion with imports pegged at
$18.88 billion, the report said.
   The Saudi news agency did not provide any breakdown of export
figures and gave only a partial list of import statistics.
   The Finance Ministry report showed 81.2 percent of Saudi Arabia's
imports last year came from 15 countries, headed by Japan, the
United States, Britain, West Germany and Italy.
   Imports from Arab League states last year increased by 8.6
percent over the preceding year, while imports from non-Arab Islamic
states increased by 9.8 percent.
   The oil-rich kingdom's major import categories all rose last
year, at least in value. The agency report only cited import values.
   They were listed as foodstuffs and livestock, which increased by
7.2 percent in value, beverages and tobacco by 12 percent, raw
materials by 21.6 percent, vegetable oils and fats by 10.4 percent,
machinery and transport equipment by 2.1 percent, furniture,
clothing and shoes by 5.7 percent.
   Saudi Arabia sits on almost one-third of the world's proven oil
reserves, but has been hard hit by a weak world oil market since the
early 1980s.
   Saudi Arabia has a population of around 12 million, including an
estimated 3 million expatriate workers.
</TEXT>
